WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.794 --> 00:00:08.210
ANURAG WADEHRA:
Welcome, everyone.

00:00:08.210 --> 00:00:09.750
Welcome to Talks at Google.

00:00:09.750 --> 00:00:12.980
My name is Anurag Wadehra
with the Google Cloud.

00:00:12.980 --> 00:00:14.660
It's a unique occasion
and a privilege

00:00:14.660 --> 00:00:20.270
for me to host this
event for Google.

00:00:20.270 --> 00:00:23.750
I'll start with a
very simple story.

00:00:23.750 --> 00:00:25.540
I grew up in Delhi
in a household

00:00:25.540 --> 00:00:30.040
where both my grandparents
were refugees from Pakistan.

00:00:30.040 --> 00:00:34.040
So partition was not
dinnertime topic.

00:00:34.040 --> 00:00:36.430
In fact, it was a lived reality.

00:00:36.430 --> 00:00:41.080
Every day, we talked about an
uncle who didn't quite make it,

00:00:41.080 --> 00:00:44.650
an aunt who was lost
somewhere in the journey,

00:00:44.650 --> 00:00:47.480
or somebody who lost
their fortune overnight.

00:00:47.480 --> 00:00:51.640
These were the tales we grew
up with in our household.

00:00:51.640 --> 00:00:54.460
Yet, when we went
to school, there

00:00:54.460 --> 00:00:58.350
was nary a mention of
any of these realities.

00:00:58.350 --> 00:01:03.960
What we read in textbooks were
the grand history, the leaders,

00:01:03.960 --> 00:01:06.990
like Nehru, Jinnah,
Gandhi, Mountbatten,

00:01:06.990 --> 00:01:11.310
who saved us or savaged us--
depending upon the side you

00:01:11.310 --> 00:01:12.420
were on--

00:01:12.420 --> 00:01:14.820
and who delivered
us independence.

00:01:14.820 --> 00:01:18.870
All that was completely
contrary to the actual

00:01:18.870 --> 00:01:22.890
lived experiences of 10
million people or more

00:01:22.890 --> 00:01:25.880
who were displaced by partition.

00:01:25.880 --> 00:01:29.390
Fortunately, a lot has
changed in last 20 years.

00:01:29.390 --> 00:01:32.060
And I'm here to introduce
two institutions that have

00:01:32.060 --> 00:01:33.755
been doing phenomenal work.

00:01:33.755 --> 00:01:37.190
The first one is 1947
Partition Archive,

00:01:37.190 --> 00:01:40.190
that has been collecting
the stories and testimonies

00:01:40.190 --> 00:01:42.470
of the survivors of partition.

00:01:42.470 --> 00:01:45.560
And the second institution
is EnActe Arts,

00:01:45.560 --> 00:01:49.040
that has been working on some
interesting and creative ways

00:01:49.040 --> 00:01:51.510
to bring many of
these stories to life.

00:01:51.510 --> 00:01:53.960
So let's begin
with the first set

00:01:53.960 --> 00:01:59.270
of guests for the 1947 Archive.

00:01:59.270 --> 00:02:02.618
Let's roll with a video.

00:02:02.618 --> 00:02:03.284
[VIDEO PLAYBACK]

00:02:03.284 --> 00:02:06.200
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:03:06.250 --> 00:03:10.480
- I feel like I'm a
[INAUDIBLE] plant.

00:03:10.480 --> 00:03:14.530
[INAUDIBLE] can
be put here, here.

00:03:14.530 --> 00:03:15.500
I have no roots.

00:03:15.500 --> 00:03:16.468
[LAUGH]

00:03:20.340 --> 00:03:24.720
- And I remember my mother made
me sit down, tear all the bed

00:03:24.720 --> 00:03:26.130
sheets.

00:03:26.130 --> 00:03:27.300
And then I knew why.

00:03:27.300 --> 00:03:30.930
Because all these wounded
people who were coming in.

00:03:30.930 --> 00:03:35.626
She had converted one place
for clearing their wounds.

00:03:35.626 --> 00:03:38.614
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:04:34.887 --> 00:04:35.470
[END PLAYBACK]

00:04:35.470 --> 00:04:37.428
ANURAG WADEHRA: Why don't
we invite the guests?

00:04:37.428 --> 00:04:40.910
Please join, three of you.

00:04:40.910 --> 00:04:44.410
[APPLAUSE]

00:04:44.410 --> 00:04:47.920
Let me do quick introductions
to the unique guests from 1947

00:04:47.920 --> 00:04:49.510
Partition Archive.

00:04:49.510 --> 00:04:51.520
I have over here
Guneeta Singh Bella,

00:04:51.520 --> 00:04:54.830
who is currently the executive
director of 1947 Partition

00:04:54.830 --> 00:04:55.330
Archive.

00:04:55.330 --> 00:04:58.210
She was born in Delhi and
immigrated with her parents

00:04:58.210 --> 00:04:59.950
to US when she was 10.

00:04:59.950 --> 00:05:02.980
And during a trip to
Hiroshima in 2008,

00:05:02.980 --> 00:05:04.870
she was deeply moved
by the oral histories

00:05:04.870 --> 00:05:08.350
of those who survived the
atomic bombing in Japan

00:05:08.350 --> 00:05:11.140
and was inspired to begin
recording oral histories

00:05:11.140 --> 00:05:12.560
of partition witnesses.

00:05:12.560 --> 00:05:16.340
She is a condensed matter
physicist by profession,

00:05:16.340 --> 00:05:18.520
and was last seen working
on quantum interfaces

00:05:18.520 --> 00:05:21.370
at Berkeley, Lawrence
Berkeley Lab.

00:05:21.370 --> 00:05:25.220
In 2013, she began volunteering
full time for the archive.

00:05:25.220 --> 00:05:28.060
Today, with nearly
5,000 oral histories

00:05:28.060 --> 00:05:30.580
of witnesses from 12
countries have been recorded,

00:05:30.580 --> 00:05:32.510
making it the largest
oral history effort

00:05:32.510 --> 00:05:35.110
for South Asian subcontinent.

00:05:35.110 --> 00:05:36.650
The other two guests are--

00:05:36.650 --> 00:05:37.150
[APPLAUSE]

00:05:37.150 --> 00:05:38.441
GUNEETA SINGH BELLA: Thank you.

00:05:38.441 --> 00:05:41.380
ANURAG WADEHRA: The other two
guests are citizen historians.

00:05:41.380 --> 00:05:42.940
And we'll learn more about that.

00:05:42.940 --> 00:05:45.830
Reena Kapoor has been a
founding donor to '47 Archive

00:05:45.830 --> 00:05:47.650
since the year of its inception.

00:05:47.650 --> 00:05:50.110
She became involved
as a citizen historian

00:05:50.110 --> 00:05:52.660
after she heard
Guneeta talk about it

00:05:52.660 --> 00:05:55.600
at the end of a play
on partition in 2011.

00:05:55.600 --> 00:05:57.640
Being a child of partition
refugees herself,

00:05:57.640 --> 00:05:59.410
Reena finds her
bliss in interviewing

00:05:59.410 --> 00:06:02.711
elders who were witnesses
and survivors to this event.

00:06:02.711 --> 00:06:04.210
Professionally, she
makes her living

00:06:04.210 --> 00:06:05.584
as a product
management executive

00:06:05.584 --> 00:06:07.370
and lives in the Bay Area.

00:06:07.370 --> 00:06:11.350
Farhana Afroz is from Bangladesh
and a software test engineer

00:06:11.350 --> 00:06:12.550
working in the Bay Area.

00:06:12.550 --> 00:06:15.430
She learned about the
'47 Archive from a flyer

00:06:15.430 --> 00:06:21.130
at a local grocery store that
read 1947 Partition Archive--

00:06:21.130 --> 00:06:23.140
share, collect, and donate.

00:06:23.140 --> 00:06:25.660
Her journey with the archive
started as a citizen historian

00:06:25.660 --> 00:06:27.130
in 2011.

00:06:27.130 --> 00:06:30.340
She has collected over 100
stories personally so far.

00:06:30.340 --> 00:06:33.820
She has recorded stories in
US as well as in Bangladesh,

00:06:33.820 --> 00:06:35.740
and she is also a
founding donor and a board

00:06:35.740 --> 00:06:36.824
member of the Archive.

00:06:36.824 --> 00:06:37.990
Welcome to all three of you.

00:06:37.990 --> 00:06:39.110
GUNEETA SINGH BELLA: Thank you.

00:06:39.110 --> 00:06:41.068
ANURAG WADEHRA: Let me
start with you, Guneeta.

00:06:41.068 --> 00:06:43.840
So, tell us about
how this all started

00:06:43.840 --> 00:06:46.687
and where did the idea come from
and how did it take this form?

00:06:46.687 --> 00:06:47.770
GUNEETA SINGH BELLA: Yeah.

00:06:47.770 --> 00:06:50.530
So I come from a
partition-affected family.

00:06:50.530 --> 00:06:55.310
My grandparents migrated from
what's now Lahore in Pakistan

00:06:55.310 --> 00:06:57.749
to Amritsar in Punjab.

00:06:57.749 --> 00:06:59.290
So I had grown up
with those stories.

00:06:59.290 --> 00:07:01.040
I come from an army
family-- very familiar

00:07:01.040 --> 00:07:03.190
with the India-Pakistan
tensions.

00:07:03.190 --> 00:07:05.410
And one of the things
that happened, when I

00:07:05.410 --> 00:07:06.730
moved to the US when I was 10.

00:07:06.730 --> 00:07:07.990
I went to high school here.

00:07:07.990 --> 00:07:09.819
It wasn't even mentioned
in my textbooks.

00:07:09.819 --> 00:07:11.860
And I knew it was a big
deal, because I had heard

00:07:11.860 --> 00:07:14.780
my grandparents--
hi, [INAUDIBLE]----

00:07:14.780 --> 00:07:16.907
I had heard my
grandparents talk about it.

00:07:16.907 --> 00:07:18.490
And they had talked
about the millions

00:07:18.490 --> 00:07:19.990
of people that were affected.

00:07:19.990 --> 00:07:21.490
And so there was
that discrepancy.

00:07:21.490 --> 00:07:23.470
When I talked about
it to my teacher,

00:07:23.470 --> 00:07:25.369
she said, oh, well,
it must not have

00:07:25.369 --> 00:07:27.910
been a big deal, because it's
not mentioned in our textbooks.

00:07:27.910 --> 00:07:30.100
So I knew something needed to
be done way back in high school,

00:07:30.100 --> 00:07:31.280
I just never knew what.

00:07:31.280 --> 00:07:33.630
And the spark came--

00:07:33.630 --> 00:07:38.050
the a-ha moment was
in Japan in 2008.

00:07:38.050 --> 00:07:40.450
I was in Hiroshima, and
I saw the Peace Memorial,

00:07:40.450 --> 00:07:42.700
and I saw the oral
history archives.

00:07:42.700 --> 00:07:45.140
And I found them to
be extremely powerful.

00:07:45.140 --> 00:07:47.140
And I realized that
those testimonies

00:07:47.140 --> 00:07:52.070
gave the bombing of Hiroshima
legitimacy and importance.

00:07:52.070 --> 00:07:55.205
And that's kind of
how it was documented.

00:07:55.205 --> 00:07:56.830
That's what inspired
the documentation.

00:07:56.830 --> 00:07:57.500
That's what we needed
to do [INAUDIBLE]..

00:07:57.500 --> 00:07:59.100
ANURAG WADEHRA:
[INAUDIBLE] the slides

00:07:59.100 --> 00:08:02.346
you want to show to [INAUDIBLE]
us on some of these incidents?

00:08:02.346 --> 00:08:04.720
GUNEETA SINGH BELLA: So yeah,
if you imagine for a second

00:08:04.720 --> 00:08:06.520
if Hiroshima had
not been documented

00:08:06.520 --> 00:08:08.560
and the Holocaust had
not been documented,

00:08:08.560 --> 00:08:12.700
we'd be in a very, very
different world today.

00:08:12.700 --> 00:08:16.320
For instance, the UNHCR was
inspired from the work done

00:08:16.320 --> 00:08:18.250
with the Holocaust survivors.

00:08:18.250 --> 00:08:20.140
And the nuclear
nonproliferation movements

00:08:20.140 --> 00:08:22.790
came from the work
done in Hiroshima.

00:08:22.790 --> 00:08:24.730
Here's partition by the numbers.

00:08:24.730 --> 00:08:26.830
14.5 million people
approximately--

00:08:26.830 --> 00:08:31.060
the latest numbers--
migrated in '46 through '48.

00:08:31.060 --> 00:08:33.370
About 20,000, if you look
at the next 10 years.

00:08:33.370 --> 00:08:36.039
That's about 1% of the world's
population at that time.

00:08:36.039 --> 00:08:38.487
So one in 100
people in the world

00:08:38.487 --> 00:08:39.570
migrated, became refugees.

00:08:39.570 --> 00:08:40.700
ANURAG WADEHRA:
20 million total.

00:08:40.700 --> 00:08:41.783
GUNEETA SINGH BELLA: Yeah.

00:08:41.783 --> 00:08:45.170
And if you extrapolate to today,
that's going to be 70 million.

00:08:45.170 --> 00:08:47.030
That's incredible.

00:08:47.030 --> 00:08:49.084
So the number of people
affected-- about 14%

00:08:49.084 --> 00:08:51.500
of the world's population, if
you look at the entire South

00:08:51.500 --> 00:08:52.479
Asian subcontinent.

00:08:52.479 --> 00:08:54.270
People don't think
everything was affected.

00:08:54.270 --> 00:08:57.170
Everywhere, there was
impacts of partition.

00:08:57.170 --> 00:08:59.120
But from our oral
histories, we know

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:01.250
that every corner
of South Asia saw

00:09:01.250 --> 00:09:09.110
some sort of influx or refugees
coming in or out, basically.

00:09:09.110 --> 00:09:12.412
We don't even know how many
people died during partition.

00:09:12.412 --> 00:09:13.870
I already told you
the Japan story,

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:15.560
so we'll skip this slide.

00:09:15.560 --> 00:09:17.630
But ultimately,
what we needed to do

00:09:17.630 --> 00:09:20.720
was record as many oral
histories as fast as possible.

00:09:20.720 --> 00:09:23.270
And we needed to reach
a diaspora of people

00:09:23.270 --> 00:09:24.570
all over the world.

00:09:24.570 --> 00:09:27.890
And so we leveraged modern
technology at the time

00:09:27.890 --> 00:09:32.660
in 2009, 2010, and we started
to crowdsource oral histories

00:09:32.660 --> 00:09:35.400
by teaching people everywhere
how to record stories.

00:09:35.400 --> 00:09:38.630
And so we democratized the
recording of South Asia's

00:09:38.630 --> 00:09:40.260
history in that way.

00:09:40.260 --> 00:09:43.070
And so if you go to our website,
you'll see this Google Map.

00:09:43.070 --> 00:09:46.130
So thanks, guys, for whoever
works on Google Maps.

00:09:46.130 --> 00:09:48.350
You can check out
some of the stories.

00:09:48.350 --> 00:09:50.600
You can click on, say, a city.

00:09:50.600 --> 00:09:53.810
You'll see stories from that
city pop up on the right.

00:09:53.810 --> 00:09:55.880
And then as you
go further, you'll

00:09:55.880 --> 00:09:57.860
see that if you click
on one of the stories,

00:09:57.860 --> 00:10:00.764
you can watch a little
snippet of the video.

00:10:00.764 --> 00:10:02.180
The full videos
actually are being

00:10:02.180 --> 00:10:05.320
stored at Stanford
University Libraries,

00:10:05.320 --> 00:10:08.140
and you can access
them there slowly.

00:10:08.140 --> 00:10:10.510
And you can see an
excerpt of the story.

00:10:10.510 --> 00:10:12.520
The goal is to record
10,000 oral histories.

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:16.090
And together, all of us who are
volunteering to do this work

00:10:16.090 --> 00:10:19.670
are going to make that
happen with your support.

00:10:19.670 --> 00:10:22.080
So far, we're at 5,000.

00:10:22.080 --> 00:10:24.640
We've recorded 5,000 oral
histories, which is already

00:10:24.640 --> 00:10:27.310
immense, because it makes it
one of the largest oral history

00:10:27.310 --> 00:10:30.150
projects coming
out of South Asia,

00:10:30.150 --> 00:10:31.960
and one of the largest
video-based projects

00:10:31.960 --> 00:10:33.260
in the world.

00:10:33.260 --> 00:10:35.140
So each of those stories
is about two hours.

00:10:35.140 --> 00:10:37.360
You can imagine how
much video that is.

00:10:37.360 --> 00:10:40.070
About 550 people have
helped record them

00:10:40.070 --> 00:10:43.720
from over 300 cities around
the world in 12 countries, 22

00:10:43.720 --> 00:10:46.570
languages, and 3/4
of a million people

00:10:46.570 --> 00:10:50.240
are following these
stories on social media.

00:10:50.240 --> 00:10:53.320
So the stories can also be
found in a number of libraries

00:10:53.320 --> 00:10:54.940
across South Asia pretty soon.

00:10:54.940 --> 00:10:57.960
That's something we're
working on with Tata Trusts.

00:10:57.960 --> 00:10:59.316
So I'm going to go ahead and--

00:10:59.316 --> 00:11:01.774
ANURAG WADEHRA: So let me turn
that next question to Reena.

00:11:01.774 --> 00:11:03.960
Reena, what's your
connection to partition

00:11:03.960 --> 00:11:07.359
and why did you become
a citizen historian?

00:11:07.359 --> 00:11:08.150
REENA KAPOOR: Yeah.

00:11:08.150 --> 00:11:12.060
So as it has been said
by a couple of you,

00:11:12.060 --> 00:11:14.970
my family was also affected
greatly by partition.

00:11:14.970 --> 00:11:17.520
Both my parents were
children when the families

00:11:17.520 --> 00:11:21.360
were forced to flee from
what was, at the time,

00:11:21.360 --> 00:11:24.210
undivided India,
but is now Pakistan.

00:11:24.210 --> 00:11:27.000
And my mother's
family, in particular--

00:11:27.000 --> 00:11:29.760
my grandmother was a
young widow at the time,

00:11:29.760 --> 00:11:30.720
it just so happened.

00:11:30.720 --> 00:11:32.820
And she pretty much
fled with four children

00:11:32.820 --> 00:11:35.550
and absolutely nothing on her.

00:11:35.550 --> 00:11:40.020
And I grew up hearing all these
stories and how many people

00:11:40.020 --> 00:11:42.960
were lost and
family members that

00:11:42.960 --> 00:11:45.420
lost their lives, lost
their livelihoods,

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:51.000
and any assets that they owned.

00:11:51.000 --> 00:11:53.640
My grandmother was sort
of a legend in the family,

00:11:53.640 --> 00:11:57.450
also, because she was
one of those people who

00:11:57.450 --> 00:12:00.480
got on a train, one of those
legendary trains, which

00:12:00.480 --> 00:12:02.760
basically showed up on either
side, on the India side

00:12:02.760 --> 00:12:05.160
and also on the Pakistan
side, filled with dead bodies,

00:12:05.160 --> 00:12:06.990
because people were massacred.

00:12:06.990 --> 00:12:09.060
And she traveled
those trains twice,

00:12:09.060 --> 00:12:11.340
once to bring her children
to the India side,

00:12:11.340 --> 00:12:15.822
and then the second time to go
back all the way to Peshawar

00:12:15.822 --> 00:12:18.030
because they were from that
Northwest frontier, which

00:12:18.030 --> 00:12:22.470
even today is a troubled
area, to bring some assets so

00:12:22.470 --> 00:12:24.270
that she could
raise her children.

00:12:24.270 --> 00:12:28.590
And she actually managed
to do that successfully,

00:12:28.590 --> 00:12:31.270
pretending to be a dead
body on those trains.

00:12:31.270 --> 00:12:34.030
So for good reason, she
was considered a legend.

00:12:34.030 --> 00:12:36.030
And I grew up hearing
these stories.

00:12:36.030 --> 00:12:38.910
I also grew up hearing
about a lot of animosity

00:12:38.910 --> 00:12:41.160
toward the other side.

00:12:41.160 --> 00:12:43.920
And as has been
said before, there

00:12:43.920 --> 00:12:46.590
was not much in our textbooks
except for the glorification

00:12:46.590 --> 00:12:48.480
of our political leaders.

00:12:48.480 --> 00:12:52.380
And the story of partition
that I heard from textbooks--

00:12:52.380 --> 00:12:55.080
and there was very little by
way of really accurate history

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:57.360
books at the time--

00:12:57.360 --> 00:12:59.430
was very divorced
from the reality

00:12:59.430 --> 00:13:01.560
of people on the ground.

00:13:01.560 --> 00:13:05.970
And when I grew up, I started
to read various accounts.

00:13:05.970 --> 00:13:09.750
And if any of you are interested
in partition, an excellent book

00:13:09.750 --> 00:13:14.650
by Urvashi Butalia, which is
"The Other Side of Silence."

00:13:14.650 --> 00:13:16.950
She was amongst the first
people to actually record

00:13:16.950 --> 00:13:17.590
oral histories.

00:13:17.590 --> 00:13:18.840
And her book is based on that.

00:13:18.840 --> 00:13:22.110
And when I read that, I
realized that what had happened

00:13:22.110 --> 00:13:27.330
to people on the ground was
very different than what

00:13:27.330 --> 00:13:31.375
had been sold to the people as
the causality of this event.

00:13:31.375 --> 00:13:33.000
And then the second
thing that happened

00:13:33.000 --> 00:13:34.920
was when I was in Delhi--

00:13:34.920 --> 00:13:39.030
I was in IIT Delhi in first
year, and it was 1984.

00:13:39.030 --> 00:13:40.980
And something very
similar happened

00:13:40.980 --> 00:13:44.370
at the time, when Indira
Gandhi was assassinated,

00:13:44.370 --> 00:13:49.680
the prime minister, and
local people attacked Sikhs.

00:13:49.680 --> 00:13:53.940
And willy-nilly mobs appeared.

00:13:53.940 --> 00:13:56.580
And there were
murders and rapes.

00:13:56.580 --> 00:13:59.730
And a lot of what I had
read about the realities

00:13:59.730 --> 00:14:01.620
of partition seemed
to be repeated.

00:14:01.620 --> 00:14:04.860
And these incidents and
the history of my family

00:14:04.860 --> 00:14:05.700
really troubled me.

00:14:05.700 --> 00:14:09.330
So in 2011, as
Anurag mentioned, I

00:14:09.330 --> 00:14:12.990
went to watch this
play, [PUNJABI] which

00:14:12.990 --> 00:14:15.810
in Punjabi means, if you haven't
seen Lahore, you haven't yet

00:14:15.810 --> 00:14:20.910
been born, which is an ode to
the glories of the old Lahore.

00:14:20.910 --> 00:14:22.860
And at the end of that--

00:14:22.860 --> 00:14:26.310
that play is about partition
and about an old lady who

00:14:26.310 --> 00:14:29.070
refuses to leave her ancestral
home after partition,

00:14:29.070 --> 00:14:31.780
which was, again, a story
I had heard many times.

00:14:31.780 --> 00:14:34.980
And Guneeta, the founder,
spoke about her vision

00:14:34.980 --> 00:14:35.700
for the archive.

00:14:35.700 --> 00:14:36.970
And I was very impressed.

00:14:36.970 --> 00:14:39.870
And I thought this is
exactly the kind of work

00:14:39.870 --> 00:14:41.850
I want to volunteer for.

00:14:41.850 --> 00:14:46.500
So since I have so much
time from my day job

00:14:46.500 --> 00:14:48.390
and being a wife
and mother, I said,

00:14:48.390 --> 00:14:51.640
why not put it all to good use
and become a citizen historian?

00:14:51.640 --> 00:14:54.570
And I've been doing that.

00:14:54.570 --> 00:14:56.220
And it has been my bliss.

00:14:56.220 --> 00:14:58.870
ANURAG WADEHRA: So what has
been some of your key insight,

00:14:58.870 --> 00:15:00.300
if you'll close off with that?

00:15:00.300 --> 00:15:01.675
REENA KAPOOR: So
obviously, there

00:15:01.675 --> 00:15:05.700
have been great learning,
just learning from our elders

00:15:05.700 --> 00:15:09.301
about what really happened and
where did these mobs come from.

00:15:09.301 --> 00:15:10.800
And one of the
questions I get asked

00:15:10.800 --> 00:15:14.190
a lot is, who were these
people who chose to kill

00:15:14.190 --> 00:15:17.550
and murder and rape and
mutilate each other?

00:15:17.550 --> 00:15:19.500
After all, Hindus
and Muslims and Sikhs

00:15:19.500 --> 00:15:22.630
had lived together
for centuries.

00:15:22.630 --> 00:15:25.002
So what went so radically wrong?

00:15:25.002 --> 00:15:26.710
And there are many,
many answers to that.

00:15:26.710 --> 00:15:28.770
But I think the
scariest of the answers,

00:15:28.770 --> 00:15:30.660
really, is that it
was people like you

00:15:30.660 --> 00:15:33.360
and me who chose
to pick up arms,

00:15:33.360 --> 00:15:37.230
chose to actually listen to
our very misguided leaders,

00:15:37.230 --> 00:15:40.230
and chose to find
differences amongst us when

00:15:40.230 --> 00:15:42.450
there were so much in common.

00:15:42.450 --> 00:15:48.120
I think if Indians meet
people from Pakistan

00:15:48.120 --> 00:15:50.370
and vice versa, I think--

00:15:50.370 --> 00:15:54.540
and also Bangladesh, as my
fellow citizen historian--

00:15:54.540 --> 00:15:57.430
and I've interviewed people
from Bengal and [INAUDIBLE]..

00:15:57.430 --> 00:16:00.209
We find we have more
in common than we

00:16:00.209 --> 00:16:01.750
do with the rest of
the world, yet we

00:16:01.750 --> 00:16:07.990
find it somehow OK
to be ready to kill

00:16:07.990 --> 00:16:11.170
for the sake of our identity.

00:16:11.170 --> 00:16:13.660
So the greatest
thing for me has been

00:16:13.660 --> 00:16:16.960
how watchful we need to
be about such forces,

00:16:16.960 --> 00:16:19.360
and how easy it is
for ordinary people

00:16:19.360 --> 00:16:23.230
to turn to violence in
the name of their tribe.

00:16:23.230 --> 00:16:24.340
So that has been great.

00:16:24.340 --> 00:16:29.080
The other insight
for me has been how

00:16:29.080 --> 00:16:30.970
remarkable that generation was.

00:16:30.970 --> 00:16:33.520
And [INAUDIBLE],, that's why I'm
such a great admirer of you,

00:16:33.520 --> 00:16:35.890
as well.

00:16:35.890 --> 00:16:36.760
Partition happened.

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:40.210
These were people who had lived
in their ancestral villages

00:16:40.210 --> 00:16:44.350
and cities and homes,
had never even traveled,

00:16:44.350 --> 00:16:46.176
had very little idea
of what was India.

00:16:46.176 --> 00:16:47.800
They thought they
were living in India.

00:16:47.800 --> 00:16:51.100
So what was Pakistan and
what was the new India?

00:16:51.100 --> 00:16:54.970
And yet they somehow found
their way to a new life

00:16:54.970 --> 00:16:58.270
and just went about surviving
and building their new lives

00:16:58.270 --> 00:17:01.330
and providing for their
children and got on with it.

00:17:01.330 --> 00:17:04.930
And it speaks to the resilience
and the remarkable nature

00:17:04.930 --> 00:17:07.369
of the people at the time.

00:17:07.369 --> 00:17:09.819
But I think what the
government ended up

00:17:09.819 --> 00:17:13.960
doing was taking that
and allowing history

00:17:13.960 --> 00:17:15.160
to be swept under the rug.

00:17:15.160 --> 00:17:18.190
And I think that is something
that we should not allow to do,

00:17:18.190 --> 00:17:21.430
because this is a history
that has repeated itself

00:17:21.430 --> 00:17:23.510
and will continue
to repeat itself.

00:17:23.510 --> 00:17:26.085
And as Guneeta
mentioned, the animosity

00:17:26.085 --> 00:17:27.460
between India and
Pakistan-- here

00:17:27.460 --> 00:17:30.045
are two nations that
still can't get past it.

00:17:30.045 --> 00:17:32.170
They're sitting there with
nuclear missiles pointed

00:17:32.170 --> 00:17:33.130
at each other.

00:17:33.130 --> 00:17:36.760
And we ought to do what we can,
even if it is by bringing forth

00:17:36.760 --> 00:17:41.200
accounts of the people who
have suffered to inform

00:17:41.200 --> 00:17:44.440
the rest of us that just
like the violence is

00:17:44.440 --> 00:17:47.157
within our power,
so is the peace.

00:17:47.157 --> 00:17:48.240
ANURAG WADEHRA: Thank you.

00:17:48.240 --> 00:17:49.160
Very well said.

00:17:49.160 --> 00:17:50.890
So I want to turn to Farhana.

00:17:50.890 --> 00:17:53.735
Farhana, you have a unique
perspective, particularly

00:17:53.735 --> 00:17:55.360
the work you've been
doing with Bengal.

00:17:55.360 --> 00:17:57.504
And Bengal often
gets less coverage

00:17:57.504 --> 00:17:59.170
when it comes to the
topic of partition.

00:17:59.170 --> 00:18:01.840
It has its unique history
related to partition.

00:18:01.840 --> 00:18:03.700
Can you share with us
some salient points

00:18:03.700 --> 00:18:05.725
about that, Bangladesh?

00:18:05.725 --> 00:18:07.240
FARHANA AFROZ: Thank you.

00:18:07.240 --> 00:18:09.650
Thank you for the kind
introduction at the beginning.

00:18:09.650 --> 00:18:13.390
Anurag said that I
am from Bangladesh.

00:18:13.390 --> 00:18:15.850
But when people ask
me where are you from,

00:18:15.850 --> 00:18:19.870
I actually tell them my
grandmother is from India.

00:18:19.870 --> 00:18:23.710
My mother was born in Pakistan,
and I was born in Bangladesh.

00:18:23.710 --> 00:18:26.410
And that's all in the
same land, Bengal.

00:18:26.410 --> 00:18:30.190
And even though none of my
family members had to migrate

00:18:30.190 --> 00:18:32.620
and we know we did not
go through the sufferings

00:18:32.620 --> 00:18:37.180
that your families did, but
our family has seen partition.

00:18:37.180 --> 00:18:39.100
And there is a profound effect--

00:18:39.100 --> 00:18:43.610
hence the identity has
changed over the years.

00:18:43.610 --> 00:18:47.200
When I first saw that flyer
about 1947 in that grocery

00:18:47.200 --> 00:18:49.990
store, the first thing
that went through my mind

00:18:49.990 --> 00:18:52.750
was, what took them so long?

00:18:52.750 --> 00:18:55.090
And later I found
out, it's not them.

00:18:55.090 --> 00:18:56.620
It's actually her.

00:18:56.620 --> 00:18:59.740
So I got involved with
the Partition Archive.

00:18:59.740 --> 00:19:02.050
I got trained as a
citizen historian.

00:19:02.050 --> 00:19:06.540
And I started recording stories
in the Bay Area, primarily.

00:19:06.540 --> 00:19:09.220
Then I went to other cities
in the United States.

00:19:09.220 --> 00:19:12.550
And then I went to
Bangladesh, actually, in 2012.

00:19:12.550 --> 00:19:16.270
I traveled to Bangladesh for
a month to collect stories.

00:19:16.270 --> 00:19:20.080
When you hear the Bengal
side of the partition,

00:19:20.080 --> 00:19:24.370
most people think, the Hindus
of East Pakistan migrated

00:19:24.370 --> 00:19:29.440
to Kolkata, and the Muslims of
Kolkata migrated to Bangladesh,

00:19:29.440 --> 00:19:30.920
and that's about it.

00:19:30.920 --> 00:19:33.130
But that is definitely
a major portion

00:19:33.130 --> 00:19:35.290
of the partition
on the Bengal side.

00:19:35.290 --> 00:19:38.670
But there is another
side of the story that

00:19:38.670 --> 00:19:40.870
are about the forgotten people.

00:19:40.870 --> 00:19:43.890
A lot of people migrated
from Bihar and Uttar Pradesh,

00:19:43.890 --> 00:19:47.440
Meghalaya, and Assam in 1947.

00:19:47.440 --> 00:19:50.550
They migrated to the
nearest part of Pakistan,

00:19:50.550 --> 00:19:54.310
which was East Pakistan
and Bangladesh today.

00:19:54.310 --> 00:19:57.460
So what happened is these people
were Urdu-speaking people,

00:19:57.460 --> 00:20:01.690
moved to East Pakistan, and it
was Pakistan and it was good.

00:20:01.690 --> 00:20:07.390
But in 24 years in 1971, East
Pakistan became Bangladesh.

00:20:07.390 --> 00:20:09.500
During the Liberation
War of Bangladesh,

00:20:09.500 --> 00:20:13.960
the Urdu-speaking community,
which was about 170,000 people

00:20:13.960 --> 00:20:16.840
at that time, sided
with the Pakistani army,

00:20:16.840 --> 00:20:19.840
because they wanted to
keep one big Pakistan.

00:20:19.840 --> 00:20:22.540
As it became Bangladesh,
now these people

00:20:22.540 --> 00:20:24.680
are kind of outsiders.

00:20:24.680 --> 00:20:26.260
They wanted to go to Pakistan.

00:20:26.260 --> 00:20:29.000
They want to migrate
to West Pakistan.

00:20:29.000 --> 00:20:31.240
Pakistan, which
is a new country--

00:20:31.240 --> 00:20:32.650
West Pakistan, I mean--

00:20:32.650 --> 00:20:38.320
was not ready to take such a
big refugees, 170,000 people.

00:20:38.320 --> 00:20:41.440
So they were left in Bangladesh
in the land of Bengal.

00:20:41.440 --> 00:20:44.380
And the Geneva
Convention put them

00:20:44.380 --> 00:20:47.650
in different refugee
camps in 1972

00:20:47.650 --> 00:20:50.890
so that they are not
attacked and they're safe.

00:20:50.890 --> 00:20:53.440
When I went to
Bangladesh in 2012,

00:20:53.440 --> 00:21:00.940
I found out there are 167
refugee camps in Bangladesh.

00:21:00.940 --> 00:21:03.160
And those Urdu-speaking
people are still

00:21:03.160 --> 00:21:05.020
living in those camps.

00:21:05.020 --> 00:21:06.910
Nobody has come for them.

00:21:06.910 --> 00:21:08.710
Nobody is willing to take them.

00:21:08.710 --> 00:21:10.940
And since they
sided with Pakistan

00:21:10.940 --> 00:21:13.690
and they identified
themselves as Pakistanis,

00:21:13.690 --> 00:21:16.990
the Bangladesh government
was not taking them, either.

00:21:16.990 --> 00:21:18.240
So these were refugees.

00:21:18.240 --> 00:21:21.820
And they were living in refugee
camps for 40-plus years.

00:21:21.820 --> 00:21:24.700
They were given a
8-by-10 room in 1972,

00:21:24.700 --> 00:21:28.240
so maybe the family was
husband and wife and a child.

00:21:28.240 --> 00:21:32.740
But by the time, in 2012,
42 years have passed,

00:21:32.740 --> 00:21:33.910
their family has grown.

00:21:33.910 --> 00:21:36.910
And they're still living
in that 8-by-10 room.

00:21:36.910 --> 00:21:38.910
And nobody is
talking about them.

00:21:38.910 --> 00:21:41.730
They're not citizens of
Pakistan or Bangladesh.

00:21:41.730 --> 00:21:43.600
They are basically stateless.

00:21:43.600 --> 00:21:45.940
So this has been going
on for a very long time.

00:21:45.940 --> 00:21:50.390
And a lot of people, especially
the Urdu-speaking community,

00:21:50.390 --> 00:21:52.990
they basically
want their rights.

00:21:52.990 --> 00:21:57.880
So in 2008, fortunately,
the Bangladesh government

00:21:57.880 --> 00:22:01.630
ruled that people who
were born after 1971, that

00:22:01.630 --> 00:22:05.590
means in Bangladesh the children
who were born in Bangladesh,

00:22:05.590 --> 00:22:09.280
will be granted the
citizenship of Bangladesh.

00:22:09.280 --> 00:22:11.090
Can you go to the
next slide, please?

00:22:11.090 --> 00:22:11.740
OK.

00:22:11.740 --> 00:22:14.470
So this is one family
that I interviewed.

00:22:14.470 --> 00:22:21.120
The lady who is second from
right, her name is Mrs.

00:22:21.120 --> 00:22:25.720
[? Khairun ?] [? Nisa. ?]
She walked from Bihar in 1947

00:22:25.720 --> 00:22:27.750
because there was a
huge riot in Bihar.

00:22:27.750 --> 00:22:29.680
We all heard about it.

00:22:29.680 --> 00:22:31.780
The lady to her right
is her daughter.

00:22:31.780 --> 00:22:33.520
She was 16 days old.

00:22:33.520 --> 00:22:36.850
She was holding her daughter and
walked all the way from Bihar

00:22:36.850 --> 00:22:38.360
to East Pakistan.

00:22:38.360 --> 00:22:39.490
And they settled.

00:22:39.490 --> 00:22:42.670
And then she had other children,
her two other daughters.

00:22:42.670 --> 00:22:46.570
But by the time 1971 happened,
now they are stateless.

00:22:46.570 --> 00:22:50.290
So this is actually a room
in Geneva camp in Dhaka,

00:22:50.290 --> 00:22:51.490
where they still live.

00:22:51.490 --> 00:22:53.170
This whole family lives there.

00:22:53.170 --> 00:22:56.600
Fortunately, their grandson,
who is not pictured here,

00:22:56.600 --> 00:23:00.340
who is 22 years old, was granted
citizenship of Bangladesh,

00:23:00.340 --> 00:23:02.560
because he was born after '72.

00:23:02.560 --> 00:23:07.210
So this was the highlight
of my trip to Bangladesh.

00:23:07.210 --> 00:23:11.260
I did interview a lot of
people, 60 stories almost,

00:23:11.260 --> 00:23:13.780
but these stories
of the refugee camps

00:23:13.780 --> 00:23:17.710
really stayed with
me, because these are

00:23:17.710 --> 00:23:19.540
the people who are forgotten.

00:23:19.540 --> 00:23:21.220
Slowly, they're
getting their rights.

00:23:21.220 --> 00:23:25.330
But they are really
stateless people to this day.

00:23:25.330 --> 00:23:27.919
Mrs. [? Khairun ?] [? Nisa ?]
doesn't have citizenship.

00:23:27.919 --> 00:23:29.960
ANURAG WADEHRA: Very
powerful and very sad story.

00:23:29.960 --> 00:23:31.210
Thank you for sharing that.

00:23:31.210 --> 00:23:33.190
Just in closing, can
you please share with us

00:23:33.190 --> 00:23:35.380
some insights you have
from the work you've

00:23:35.380 --> 00:23:40.450
been doing after 70
years of partition,

00:23:40.450 --> 00:23:41.997
if you could
summarize that for us?

00:23:41.997 --> 00:23:43.330
GUNEETA SINGH BELLA: Yeah, sure.

00:23:43.330 --> 00:23:44.830
Can I share a couple of slides?

00:23:44.830 --> 00:23:46.812
So these are just
anecdotes from stories.

00:23:46.812 --> 00:23:48.520
So these stories--
one of the cool things

00:23:48.520 --> 00:23:50.228
is not only do you
learn about partition,

00:23:50.228 --> 00:23:53.530
but you learn about
pre-partition culture, cultures

00:23:53.530 --> 00:23:55.325
that are now becoming obsolete.

00:23:55.325 --> 00:23:57.700
So here's a gentleman we had
interviewed, actually, right

00:23:57.700 --> 00:23:59.590
here in Rodeo in the Bay Area.

00:23:59.590 --> 00:24:01.810
He was 107 at the time.

00:24:01.810 --> 00:24:04.240
He's not alive any longer.

00:24:04.240 --> 00:24:07.120
But he told me this one
story that really stood out.

00:24:07.120 --> 00:24:12.760
So we think of chai as a very
staple South Asian drink.

00:24:12.760 --> 00:24:15.192
But he told me about
a time in the 1920s

00:24:15.192 --> 00:24:17.650
when they used to boycott chai
because they were boycotting

00:24:17.650 --> 00:24:20.230
the East India
Company that they felt

00:24:20.230 --> 00:24:22.660
was trying to popularize
tea in an area

00:24:22.660 --> 00:24:25.342
where people didn't drink tea
in a lot of northern India.

00:24:25.342 --> 00:24:26.800
And he claimed that
they used to go

00:24:26.800 --> 00:24:29.670
around spiking people's milk.

00:24:29.670 --> 00:24:31.352
I mean, I don't know
how true that is,

00:24:31.352 --> 00:24:32.810
but that was the
rumor of the time.

00:24:32.810 --> 00:24:35.464
And so he, to this
day, did not drink tea.

00:24:35.464 --> 00:24:36.880
So I thought that
was fascinating.

00:24:36.880 --> 00:24:38.650
But of course, in
terms of partition,

00:24:38.650 --> 00:24:42.070
he did walk for miles
and miles all the way

00:24:42.070 --> 00:24:48.270
from North-West Frontier region
over to what's now India.

00:24:48.270 --> 00:24:51.190
Another impact of partition
was art and culture.

00:24:51.190 --> 00:24:56.600
So here's a photograph of a
music family, a music gharana.

00:24:56.600 --> 00:24:58.500
So a lot of music
gharanas were disrupted

00:24:58.500 --> 00:25:01.257
when musicians had to
up and leave and leave

00:25:01.257 --> 00:25:02.340
behind a lot of their art.

00:25:02.340 --> 00:25:05.929
And for instance, there's
a popular story of--

00:25:05.929 --> 00:25:07.470
there's certain
musical families that

00:25:07.470 --> 00:25:10.570
used to perform in the
Golden Temple in Punjab.

00:25:10.570 --> 00:25:12.120
And they now live in Pakistan.

00:25:12.120 --> 00:25:14.700
And they're not able
to perform any longer

00:25:14.700 --> 00:25:17.150
because they live on the
other side of the border--

00:25:17.150 --> 00:25:21.160
so fascinating histories
like that of disruption.

00:25:21.160 --> 00:25:24.340
We're also-- and by accident--
recording endangered languages.

00:25:24.340 --> 00:25:26.340
So there's a language
called [? Toregali, ?] and

00:25:26.340 --> 00:25:28.290
there's a number of
stories now in the archive

00:25:28.290 --> 00:25:30.630
because a volunteer from
the North-West Frontier

00:25:30.630 --> 00:25:33.235
region in Swat who
speaks that language

00:25:33.235 --> 00:25:35.610
decided to record stories of
his elders in that language.

00:25:35.610 --> 00:25:38.070
And there's not many
other recordings, if any,

00:25:38.070 --> 00:25:39.690
in that language.

00:25:39.690 --> 00:25:41.190
Another thing that
really stands out

00:25:41.190 --> 00:25:43.380
when you record oral
histories is the significance

00:25:43.380 --> 00:25:46.080
of the kingdoms pre-partition,
which today have been

00:25:46.080 --> 00:25:48.070
mostly swept under the rug.

00:25:48.070 --> 00:25:50.430
So there was British India,
which is the pink region

00:25:50.430 --> 00:25:51.510
that you see on this map.

00:25:51.510 --> 00:25:57.019
And then the darker region
consists of about 560 kingdoms.

00:25:57.019 --> 00:25:57.810
And so [INAUDIBLE].

00:25:57.810 --> 00:25:59.226
ANURAG WADEHRA:
Thank you so much.

00:25:59.226 --> 00:26:02.460
I want to close off in one
short video that sums up

00:26:02.460 --> 00:26:04.189
the observations, if I may.

00:26:04.189 --> 00:26:04.855
