00:29:25.540 --> 00:29:26.980
What does EnActe do?

00:29:26.980 --> 00:29:28.780
We tell stories.

00:29:28.780 --> 00:29:32.230
We create contemporary
theatrical storytelling

00:29:32.230 --> 00:29:34.930
projects that start
conversations,

00:29:34.930 --> 00:29:38.620
that start conversations about
our history, about our culture,

00:29:38.620 --> 00:29:42.460
about our religions, and
essentially about our place

00:29:42.460 --> 00:29:45.520
as South Asians in
global society today.

00:29:45.520 --> 00:29:48.730
We are the people who--

00:29:48.730 --> 00:29:53.380
because we are in America,
we are an immigrant community

00:29:53.380 --> 00:29:54.670
in America--

00:29:54.670 --> 00:29:59.770
we create a platform that
allows the next generation

00:29:59.770 --> 00:30:05.740
to embrace who they are
and where they came from

00:30:05.740 --> 00:30:09.250
and give them the tools to
create a new culture that

00:30:09.250 --> 00:30:12.350
is an amalgamation of the
culture that they came from

00:30:12.350 --> 00:30:15.280
and the land that
they live in now.

00:30:15.280 --> 00:30:17.260
So that's EnActe Arts.

00:30:17.260 --> 00:30:18.930
We do theatrical projects.

00:30:18.930 --> 00:30:21.160
Noorani Dance has
the same mission,

00:30:21.160 --> 00:30:22.450
but they do it through dance.

00:30:22.450 --> 00:30:25.990
The founder of Noorani Dance
is in Pakistan right now.

00:30:25.990 --> 00:30:28.210
She is born and brought
up in the Bay Area.

00:30:28.210 --> 00:30:30.040
Her name is Farah
Yasmeen Shaikh.

00:30:30.040 --> 00:30:34.780
And she is, as we speak,
performing a dance piece

00:30:34.780 --> 00:30:37.870
on the story on the life
of Noor Jahan in Lahore,

00:30:37.870 --> 00:30:39.220
where Noor Jahan was buried.

00:30:39.220 --> 00:30:41.740
So we not only
create stories here,

00:30:41.740 --> 00:30:45.940
we take them back to
where they belong.

00:30:45.940 --> 00:30:51.250
There's a few things about us
as a South Asian population

00:30:51.250 --> 00:30:55.275
in the diaspora out of
our own South Asian roots.

00:30:58.150 --> 00:31:00.330
The South Asians
in the Bay Area--

00:31:00.330 --> 00:31:05.360
we tend to follow the
three gods of education.

00:31:05.360 --> 00:31:09.200
And the three gods of education
are doctor, lawyer, engineer.

00:31:09.200 --> 00:31:11.400
[LAUGHTER]

00:31:11.400 --> 00:31:13.730
Some of us have a
[? kick in the step. ?]

00:31:13.730 --> 00:31:18.930
However, following the three
gods of education-- doctor,

00:31:18.930 --> 00:31:22.440
lawyer, engineer-- means that
we have become a model minority

00:31:22.440 --> 00:31:23.910
in countries like the US.

00:31:23.910 --> 00:31:24.840
We behave ourselves.

00:31:24.840 --> 00:31:26.100
We own a fair amount of money.

00:31:26.100 --> 00:31:30.440
We look good on paper.

00:31:30.440 --> 00:31:32.370
What we don't stop
to think about

00:31:32.370 --> 00:31:38.490
is that the children that
are born to these three gods

00:31:38.490 --> 00:31:43.410
are not necessarily using the
same filter that was applied

00:31:43.410 --> 00:31:44.620
to the people who came here.

00:31:44.620 --> 00:31:46.360
They're a normal population.

00:31:46.360 --> 00:31:49.680
So there are as many
dancers, actors, artists,

00:31:49.680 --> 00:31:52.470
playwrights amongst
this population

00:31:52.470 --> 00:31:54.810
as there are in any
other normal population.

00:31:54.810 --> 00:31:57.000
And who is serving that need?

00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.190
Well, that is us.

00:31:59.190 --> 00:32:01.350
So what do we do?

00:32:01.350 --> 00:32:03.780
In the environment
that we live in,

00:32:03.780 --> 00:32:07.050
there are three kinds of
storytellers that we have--

00:32:07.050 --> 00:32:10.050
the professional storytellers.

00:32:10.050 --> 00:32:11.690
There is Kunal in
the background here.

00:32:11.690 --> 00:32:12.930
There he is, Kunal.

00:32:12.930 --> 00:32:15.450
He's a professional actor.

00:32:15.450 --> 00:32:16.950
He is making his way.

00:32:16.950 --> 00:32:18.940
He is an integral
part of EnActe.

00:32:18.940 --> 00:32:20.150
He actually works at EnActe.

00:32:20.150 --> 00:32:21.880
He's our marketing manager.

00:32:21.880 --> 00:32:23.220
He's a professional actor.

00:32:23.220 --> 00:32:26.370
And talk to him about his story.

00:32:26.370 --> 00:32:29.760
That's one kind of storyteller.

00:32:29.760 --> 00:32:31.440
There is a second
kind of storyteller

00:32:31.440 --> 00:32:36.630
that is a wannabe, somebody
who wants to be in the arts

00:32:36.630 --> 00:32:38.250
but needs the training.

00:32:38.250 --> 00:32:42.030
Then there is a third kind
of performer, actor, theater

00:32:42.030 --> 00:32:46.530
person who we call the
second career person.

00:32:46.530 --> 00:32:49.860
That's the Googlers
in the room who,

00:32:49.860 --> 00:32:54.330
in their copious amounts of free
time, go into community theater

00:32:54.330 --> 00:32:55.560
somewhere.

00:32:55.560 --> 00:33:00.090
So EnActe is one of the only
theater companies in the US,

00:33:00.090 --> 00:33:03.360
that actually caters to
all three kinds of talents.

00:33:03.360 --> 00:33:05.950
We have aspire productions
for community theaters.

00:33:05.950 --> 00:33:07.650
We have hybrid productions.

00:33:07.650 --> 00:33:09.490
And we have professional
productions.

00:33:09.490 --> 00:33:12.630
Our professional productions
tend to be large.

00:33:12.630 --> 00:33:16.350
We collaborate with a lot of
people, especially musicians

00:33:16.350 --> 00:33:19.410
and dancers, because in
the South Asian tradition

00:33:19.410 --> 00:33:23.430
of storytelling, it's
almost impossible

00:33:23.430 --> 00:33:27.630
to tell the story without the
dance and the music associated

00:33:27.630 --> 00:33:29.710
with the flavor of that story.

00:33:29.710 --> 00:33:34.120
So I'm going to talk to you a
little bit about "The Parting,"

00:33:34.120 --> 00:33:40.200
which is a play which tells
the story of the partition.

00:33:40.200 --> 00:33:42.450
Guneeta and all the
citizen historians

00:33:42.450 --> 00:33:46.650
have done such an incredible
job of capturing these stories.

00:33:46.650 --> 00:33:51.630
It is now our job to bring these
stories to where all of you

00:33:51.630 --> 00:33:53.340
are.

00:33:53.340 --> 00:33:59.700
And as they mentioned, the
stories, the historic accuracy

00:33:59.700 --> 00:34:04.710
of that period does not
come from the political

00:34:04.710 --> 00:34:12.090
and the party line briefs
that were given to us.

00:34:12.090 --> 00:34:14.400
The British cannot
write that story.

00:34:14.400 --> 00:34:16.620
[INAUDIBLE] cannot
write that story.

00:34:16.620 --> 00:34:20.610
That story is written by
the people who experienced,

00:34:20.610 --> 00:34:24.120
who stepped across that line
that was made in such a hurry

00:34:24.120 --> 00:34:30.150
and found themselves in their
own country to be refugees.

00:34:30.150 --> 00:34:32.600
That's the story
we want to tell.

00:34:32.600 --> 00:34:35.270
But today, I am
going to tell you

00:34:35.270 --> 00:34:42.350
a story that sort of
encapsulates everything

00:34:42.350 --> 00:34:43.350
that we're trying to do.

00:34:43.350 --> 00:34:47.290
And I want to bring on stage a
very special person, Mr. Ravi

00:34:47.290 --> 00:34:48.488
Chopra.

00:34:48.488 --> 00:34:50.883
[APPLAUSE]

00:34:56.152 --> 00:34:58.269
RAVI CHOPRA: [INAUDIBLE]

00:34:58.269 --> 00:35:00.310
VINITA SUD BELANI: Ravi
ji is very special to us.

00:35:00.310 --> 00:35:04.760
He has been an actor with
us for a very long time.

00:35:04.760 --> 00:35:06.910
I am not going to give an
introduction to Ravi ji.

00:35:06.910 --> 00:35:09.310
We are just going to jump
straight into his story.

00:35:09.310 --> 00:35:13.340
And you're going to
know why as we talk.

00:35:13.340 --> 00:35:19.510
So Ravi ji, tell me, when
and where were you born?

00:35:19.510 --> 00:35:24.880
RAVI CHOPRA: Vinita, I was
born in very famous place known

00:35:24.880 --> 00:35:29.780
all over the world,
Lahore, in the year 1938.

00:35:29.780 --> 00:35:30.932
VINITA SUD BELANI: 1938.

00:35:30.932 --> 00:35:32.390
So you were about
eight and a half,

00:35:32.390 --> 00:35:34.430
almost nine, when
partition happened.

00:35:34.430 --> 00:35:35.240
RAVI CHOPRA: Yeah.

00:35:35.240 --> 00:35:37.980
VINITA SUD BELANI: So where
were you living at that time?

00:35:37.980 --> 00:35:42.870
RAVI CHOPRA: I was living with
my grandmother and my younger

00:35:42.870 --> 00:35:46.980
brother in a village
known as [INAUDIBLE]..

00:35:46.980 --> 00:35:48.390
It was then a small village.

00:35:48.390 --> 00:35:51.688
Today, it may be a big town.

00:35:51.688 --> 00:35:54.820
VINITA SUD BELANI:
And when in 1947--

00:35:54.820 --> 00:35:56.940
what were you doing
there in the village?

00:35:56.940 --> 00:36:01.640
RAVI CHOPRA: So I used to go
to [INAUDIBLE],, the school,

00:36:01.640 --> 00:36:05.040
and learn Urdu from a Maulvi--

00:36:05.040 --> 00:36:13.050
Maulvi means teacher--
and lead a normal life.

00:36:13.050 --> 00:36:18.410
My father was the in charge
police station [INAUDIBLE]..

00:36:18.410 --> 00:36:21.590
He got his orders for
promotion to the next track.

00:36:21.590 --> 00:36:26.130
That is [? sub-inspector. ?]
And he had to go to [INAUDIBLE]..

00:36:26.130 --> 00:36:30.190
So he left us under the
care of one local merchant,

00:36:30.190 --> 00:36:34.260
[INAUDIBLE],, to look
after us in his absence.

00:36:34.260 --> 00:36:37.450
And that he would come back
in a month and a half or so,

00:36:37.450 --> 00:36:40.240
and he would take us to India.

00:36:40.240 --> 00:36:43.120
My mother and sister, they
had already gone to India.

00:36:43.120 --> 00:36:46.184
So that was the kind of
scenario at that time.

00:36:46.184 --> 00:36:47.100
VINITA SUD BELANI: OK.

00:36:47.100 --> 00:36:53.580
So what made you
leave [INAUDIBLE]??

00:36:53.580 --> 00:36:55.440
RAVI CHOPRA: As I
mentioned, we were leading

00:36:55.440 --> 00:36:56.820
just normal life, no worries.

00:36:56.820 --> 00:36:58.380
We were small kids--

00:36:58.380 --> 00:37:02.160
going to school, coming back,
playing with the friends.

00:37:02.160 --> 00:37:05.260
And then one fine
morning, the [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:05.260 --> 00:37:07.750
of the police station, that's
number two of the police

00:37:07.750 --> 00:37:09.830
station.

00:37:09.830 --> 00:37:12.190
He came to [INAUDIBLE]
and warned him

00:37:12.190 --> 00:37:16.360
that his host is going to
be attacked that night.

00:37:16.360 --> 00:37:20.170
and so he should leave
as soon as possible.

00:37:20.170 --> 00:37:21.850
He took it seriously.

00:37:21.850 --> 00:37:25.510
And he collected
all his valuables--

00:37:25.510 --> 00:37:30.010
cash, jewelry,
important documents.

00:37:30.010 --> 00:37:32.650
And many of them,
even, they tried

00:37:32.650 --> 00:37:37.390
to hide it under the
clothing, all over the body.

00:37:37.390 --> 00:37:41.290
And when the darkness came,
we went to the [INAUDIBLE]

00:37:41.290 --> 00:37:42.390
railway station.

00:37:42.390 --> 00:37:44.340
This was a village,
only passenger trains

00:37:44.340 --> 00:37:46.670
would stop there.

00:37:46.670 --> 00:37:50.010
So this [INAUDIBLE],, I think
that he rightly thought that

00:37:50.010 --> 00:37:53.450
if we get the passenger train,
it's going to stop at every

00:37:53.450 --> 00:37:55.070
station, which was very--

00:37:55.070 --> 00:37:57.320
it was not safe, very risky.

00:37:57.320 --> 00:38:02.280
So he went the opposite
direction, to a junction town,

00:38:02.280 --> 00:38:02.884
[INAUDIBLE].

00:38:02.884 --> 00:38:04.550
From there, we got
the [INAUDIBLE] train

00:38:04.550 --> 00:38:05.930
so that we don't have to stop.

00:38:05.930 --> 00:38:07.430
We only stop at the
junction station

00:38:07.430 --> 00:38:08.972
and not at every
village station.

00:38:08.972 --> 00:38:10.430
VINITA SUD BELANI:
So when you were

00:38:10.430 --> 00:38:11.930
going in the opposite
direction, you

00:38:11.930 --> 00:38:14.550
must have passed
[INAUDIBLE] village.

00:38:14.550 --> 00:38:16.100
RAVI CHOPRA: Yes.

00:38:16.100 --> 00:38:18.470
We passed through
the Kasur village.

00:38:18.470 --> 00:38:22.880
And [INAUDIBLE] was sitting
right next to the window.

00:38:22.880 --> 00:38:28.160
And I distinctly remember
him shouting, [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:28.160 --> 00:38:32.270
And we also [INAUDIBLE] we
saw fire almost everywhere

00:38:32.270 --> 00:38:34.590
in our village where
we were staying.

00:38:34.590 --> 00:38:36.945
And he was literally
in tears when

00:38:36.945 --> 00:38:39.810
he reached the next
junction station [INAUDIBLE]

00:38:39.810 --> 00:38:43.814
from where we were to catch
the train to India [INAUDIBLE]..

00:38:43.814 --> 00:38:46.230
VINITA SUD BELANI: So what
happened on arrival in station,

00:38:46.230 --> 00:38:46.729
then?

00:38:50.870 --> 00:38:55.472
RAVI CHOPRA: [INAUDIBLE]
you see, this place,

00:38:55.472 --> 00:38:56.930
when we are waiting
for the train--

00:38:56.930 --> 00:38:58.179
because trains had no timings.

00:38:58.179 --> 00:38:59.344
There's no timetable sheet.

00:38:59.344 --> 00:39:00.760
That train will
come in yesterday,

00:39:00.760 --> 00:39:02.602
the train will come today.

00:39:02.602 --> 00:39:04.060
That kind of
scenario [INAUDIBLE]..

00:39:04.060 --> 00:39:05.900
So we were just
waiting for the train.

00:39:05.900 --> 00:39:09.800
And then suddenly
the firing started.

00:39:09.800 --> 00:39:11.920
And all the people
on the platform,

00:39:11.920 --> 00:39:14.790
we started running
to find the cover.

00:39:14.790 --> 00:39:18.990
And in the process, a
bullet hit me on my calf

00:39:18.990 --> 00:39:21.710
and I started bleeding.

00:39:21.710 --> 00:39:25.110
And then my [INAUDIBLE],,
very courageous lady

00:39:25.110 --> 00:39:27.940
with a good presence
of mind, she

00:39:27.940 --> 00:39:32.110
thought of her [? duties. ?]
Sterilize with her urine,

00:39:32.110 --> 00:39:34.120
and made it a
bandage on my wound.

00:39:34.120 --> 00:39:37.710
And we were hiding
behind a pillar.

00:39:37.710 --> 00:39:41.570
VINITA SUD BELANI: And did
you make it onto the train?

00:39:41.570 --> 00:39:43.532
RAVI CHOPRA: Yes,
we did, but when

00:39:43.532 --> 00:39:48.630
the train came, as you
see on the pictures here,

00:39:48.630 --> 00:39:54.500
it was fully packed, people
sitting on the top of the roof,

00:39:54.500 --> 00:39:57.100
even in the couplings
of the trains,

00:39:57.100 --> 00:39:59.900
people sitting in
front of the engine.

00:39:59.900 --> 00:40:02.492
And the compartments
were totally packed.

00:40:02.492 --> 00:40:03.950
And the people on
the platform, you

00:40:03.950 --> 00:40:05.540
can just imagine [INAUDIBLE].

00:40:05.540 --> 00:40:08.210
There's no place to getting
them still, trying to find place

00:40:08.210 --> 00:40:11.660
in all that confusion.

00:40:11.660 --> 00:40:14.810
We were fortunate in the
sense that [INAUDIBLE]

00:40:14.810 --> 00:40:19.190
had known the assistant
station master [INAUDIBLE]..

00:40:19.190 --> 00:40:23.390
And he paid him a lot of
cash and money, because he

00:40:23.390 --> 00:40:26.720
had a first-class
compartment reserved to him,

00:40:26.720 --> 00:40:28.540
his family traveling to Kasur.

00:40:28.540 --> 00:40:32.350
Kasur was a border town
next to [INAUDIBLE]..

00:40:32.350 --> 00:40:35.800
So it was a border
town on Pakistan-India.

00:40:35.800 --> 00:40:38.400
And that was the only
way we could survive.

00:40:38.400 --> 00:40:42.610
So he paid whatever
he wanted so that we

00:40:42.610 --> 00:40:47.374
could be part of his family.

00:40:47.374 --> 00:40:49.790
VINITA SUD BELANI: And so you
got onto the train with him?

00:40:49.790 --> 00:40:50.498
RAVI CHOPRA: Yes.

00:40:50.498 --> 00:40:55.560
I had an assistant station
masters' family, a wife

00:40:55.560 --> 00:41:00.240
and, I think, two small kids,
[INAUDIBLE] family, myself,

00:41:00.240 --> 00:41:02.530
my younger brother,
my [INAUDIBLE]..

00:41:02.530 --> 00:41:06.290
So we all went [INAUDIBLE] into
the first-class compartment.

00:41:06.290 --> 00:41:07.410
And--

00:41:07.410 --> 00:41:09.060
VINITA SUD BELANI: What do
you remember of that journey?

00:41:09.060 --> 00:41:09.935
What do you remember?

00:41:09.935 --> 00:41:11.596
Were there stops?

00:41:11.596 --> 00:41:12.870
And between stops--

00:41:12.870 --> 00:41:15.964
RAVI CHOPRA: Stops, yes,
from [INAUDIBLE] to Kasur

00:41:15.964 --> 00:41:18.380
there were, if I remember, two
or three stops, [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:18.380 --> 00:41:20.680
stops, the train would stop.

00:41:20.680 --> 00:41:27.570
And at every stop,
there would be

00:41:27.570 --> 00:41:30.060
mobs of people coming
when the train stopped

00:41:30.060 --> 00:41:35.190
and just shouting [INAUDIBLE]
You see, they used [INAUDIBLE]..

00:41:35.190 --> 00:41:38.460
Because from India's
side, the Sikhs were--

00:41:38.460 --> 00:41:41.820
[INAUDIBLE] the Sikhs were
massacring the Muslim people.

00:41:41.820 --> 00:41:44.830
And they used to
shout on [INAUDIBLE]

00:41:44.830 --> 00:41:48.160
trying to find if any Sikh
families, [INAUDIBLE]..

00:41:48.160 --> 00:41:52.240
And our station master, he
would just open the windows.

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:54.750
He said, no, I'm
the station master.

00:41:54.750 --> 00:41:56.765
I am traveling here
with my family.

00:41:56.765 --> 00:41:59.390
And we used to hide ourselves in
the bottom and lock ourselves.

00:41:59.390 --> 00:42:03.520
[INAUDIBLE] the
first-class compartment

00:42:03.520 --> 00:42:06.160
had the bottom attached.

00:42:06.160 --> 00:42:10.090
Even until very recently,
we had the bottom attached.

00:42:10.090 --> 00:42:15.120
And that is what
[INAUDIBLE] saved us.

00:42:15.120 --> 00:42:18.540
Because he would only show his
family, his wife and children.

00:42:18.540 --> 00:42:19.530
And he had a beard.

00:42:19.530 --> 00:42:26.550
And I still remember that small
beard and kind face, because

00:42:26.550 --> 00:42:28.560
of him that we lived, too.

00:42:28.560 --> 00:42:30.810
VINITA SUD BELANI: So you
were saved by a kind Muslim.

00:42:30.810 --> 00:42:32.460
You were very fortunate.

00:42:32.460 --> 00:42:34.260
RAVI CHOPRA: Yes, absolutely.

00:42:34.260 --> 00:42:43.490
You can say that
[INAUDIBLE] And maybe

00:42:43.490 --> 00:42:45.910
I had to survive
because one day I

00:42:45.910 --> 00:42:49.229
had to serve my country
in the rank of general

00:42:49.229 --> 00:42:50.020
of the Indian army.

00:42:50.020 --> 00:42:52.050
VINITA SUD BELANI: General
of the Indian army.

00:42:52.050 --> 00:42:52.445
RAVI CHOPRA: Yes.

00:42:52.445 --> 00:42:52.840
VINITA SUD BELANI: All right.

00:42:52.840 --> 00:42:54.506
RAVI CHOPRA: That was
a different story.

00:42:54.506 --> 00:42:55.586
VINITA SUD BELANI: OK.

00:42:55.586 --> 00:42:56.960
So we'll come back
to this story.

00:42:56.960 --> 00:42:58.270
What did you see between stops?

00:42:58.270 --> 00:42:59.510
Did you look out of the window?

00:42:59.510 --> 00:43:01.635
Did you have the courage
to look out of the window?

00:43:01.635 --> 00:43:05.100
RAVI CHOPRA: As we
approaching the platform--

00:43:05.100 --> 00:43:07.470
as you were traveling
to look out the window,

00:43:07.470 --> 00:43:10.390
you would see young
girls running and jumping

00:43:10.390 --> 00:43:16.961
into the wells, young people
with murderous eyes chasing

00:43:16.961 --> 00:43:17.460
them.

00:43:17.460 --> 00:43:19.230
And they're trying
to save their honor,

00:43:19.230 --> 00:43:22.520
no option but to kill
themselves, burn themselves.

00:43:22.520 --> 00:43:25.200
And there's a fire
all over the field.

00:43:25.200 --> 00:43:28.220
I mean, there was
terrible scenes.

00:43:28.220 --> 00:43:31.730
We were not sure what
all is happening.

00:43:31.730 --> 00:43:34.850
It's only in retrospect
that they told us.

00:43:34.850 --> 00:43:38.360
And so this [INAUDIBLE] even
on the platform, [INAUDIBLE]

00:43:38.360 --> 00:43:41.360
you could see the bodies
decorated along the railroad

00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:45.400
track, literally lined up.

00:43:45.400 --> 00:43:48.782
So that was the kind of
human behavior at that time.

00:43:48.782 --> 00:43:50.490
VINITA SUD BELANI:
And what was happening

00:43:50.490 --> 00:43:51.770
inside the compartment?

00:43:51.770 --> 00:43:53.070
Where you huddled in and--

00:43:55.890 --> 00:43:58.770
RAVI CHOPRA: I mean,
as I mentioned,

00:43:58.770 --> 00:44:02.380
as far as we were
concerned, thanks

00:44:02.380 --> 00:44:05.000
to this assistant
station master,

00:44:05.000 --> 00:44:08.740
that he would every
time, he would save us,

00:44:08.740 --> 00:44:12.020
because we'd hide out in the
bottom, lock ourselves in.

00:44:12.020 --> 00:44:13.660
Only he would be visible.

00:44:13.660 --> 00:44:15.990
And even the mob will
come, peek through,

00:44:15.990 --> 00:44:19.645
make sure that there's
nobody else and go.

00:44:19.645 --> 00:44:21.520
VINITA SUD BELANI: So
when you reached Kasur,

00:44:21.520 --> 00:44:24.917
that was the last stop
before the border?

00:44:24.917 --> 00:44:25.625
RAVI CHOPRA: Yes.

00:44:25.625 --> 00:44:27.208
VINITA SUD BELANI:
What happened then?

00:44:27.208 --> 00:44:28.980
RAVI CHOPRA: Yes.

00:44:28.980 --> 00:44:35.480
Kasur-- when we reached Kasur,
this assistant station master,

00:44:35.480 --> 00:44:40.100
he opened the window and made
sure that everything's OK.

00:44:40.100 --> 00:44:42.830
Then he told his family
to get off the train.

00:44:42.830 --> 00:44:45.260
And he was going to
say bye bye to us.

00:44:45.260 --> 00:44:49.610
Then [INAUDIBLE] told him,
please don't leave us now.

00:44:49.610 --> 00:44:51.590
Let the train move.

00:44:51.590 --> 00:44:54.890
And let the train move, and
then only, you please leave.

00:44:54.890 --> 00:44:56.480
And he did that.

00:44:56.480 --> 00:45:00.170
I distinctly remembered
moving train,

00:45:00.170 --> 00:45:03.080
he jumped up almost toward
the end of the platform.

00:45:03.080 --> 00:45:05.270
And then waved at us.

00:45:05.270 --> 00:45:08.522
That kind of picture, I
still have in my mind.

00:45:08.522 --> 00:45:09.980
VINITA SUD BELANI:
What a kind man.

00:45:09.980 --> 00:45:13.062
And so you crossed the
border and you arrived at--

00:45:13.062 --> 00:45:13.770
RAVI CHOPRA: Yes.

00:45:13.770 --> 00:45:20.460
And I owe my life to two
Muslim Pakistani gentlemen.

00:45:20.460 --> 00:45:28.460
One [INAUDIBLE] who saved us,
[INAUDIBLE] assistant station

00:45:28.460 --> 00:45:32.882
master, otherwise I
wouldn't be here today.

00:45:32.882 --> 00:45:36.040
VINITA SUD BELANI: Well,
we honor those two people

00:45:36.040 --> 00:45:36.910
who saved your life.

00:45:36.910 --> 00:45:39.070
We are very happy that
you are here today.

00:45:39.070 --> 00:45:41.170
Tell us what happened when
you crossed the border

00:45:41.170 --> 00:45:43.731
and arrived at [INAUDIBLE].

00:45:43.731 --> 00:45:45.480
RAVI CHOPRA: When we
reached [INAUDIBLE],,

00:45:45.480 --> 00:45:48.710
we came out of the compartment.

00:45:48.710 --> 00:45:52.480
Believe me, there's blood
splattered on the [INAUDIBLE],,

00:45:52.480 --> 00:45:55.520
on the train compartment,
the train we were traveling,

00:45:55.520 --> 00:46:00.970
mutilated bodies, hands
hanging from the windows.

00:46:00.970 --> 00:46:03.640
This was terrible.

00:46:03.640 --> 00:46:07.040
So we were-- as I remember,
we were the only family

00:46:07.040 --> 00:46:10.500
survived the massacre.

00:46:10.500 --> 00:46:12.030
There was nobody else.

00:46:12.030 --> 00:46:13.460
VINITA SUD BELANI: Incredible.

00:46:13.460 --> 00:46:18.650
RAVI CHOPRA: And when you think
about the Sikh families who

00:46:18.650 --> 00:46:24.170
took care of us,
giving us milk, fruit,

00:46:24.170 --> 00:46:27.200
[INAUDIBLE] medical aid,
and that kind of scenario

00:46:27.200 --> 00:46:27.920
was there.

00:46:27.920 --> 00:46:32.917
And then from there we boarded
the train to go to Delhi.

00:46:32.917 --> 00:46:35.500
VINITA SUD BELANI: So you went
to Delhi because you had family

00:46:35.500 --> 00:46:36.370
in Delhi, or--

00:46:40.170 --> 00:46:43.172
RAVI CHOPRA: Because that
was the only place to go.

00:46:43.172 --> 00:46:44.630
VINITA SUD BELANI:
So what happened

00:46:44.630 --> 00:46:46.290
when you arrived at Delhi?

00:46:46.290 --> 00:46:47.790
RAVI CHOPRA: Delhi
railroad station,

00:46:47.790 --> 00:46:51.683
when we arrived,
it was jam packed.

00:46:51.683 --> 00:46:54.260
Platform was full of people.

00:46:58.445 --> 00:47:00.730
There was hardly
place even to move.

00:47:00.730 --> 00:47:03.090
So my grandmother,
holding my son,

00:47:03.090 --> 00:47:05.700
I'm limping with my leg hurt.

00:47:05.700 --> 00:47:10.140
My younger brother had a fever,
so he's also tagging along.

00:47:10.140 --> 00:47:14.190
And then [INAUDIBLE]
my brother got lost.

00:47:14.190 --> 00:47:16.160
VINITA SUD BELANI:
Oh, my goodness.

00:47:16.160 --> 00:47:19.340
RAVI CHOPRA: And I tell
you, my grandmother,

00:47:19.340 --> 00:47:26.390
shouting [INAUDIBLE]
brown hairs.

00:47:26.390 --> 00:47:27.710
Have you seen it?

00:47:27.710 --> 00:47:30.680
I was also shouting,
[INAUDIBLE],, because, I mean,

00:47:30.680 --> 00:47:34.520
just imagine having
suffered all the ordeal

00:47:34.520 --> 00:47:37.520
coming back to the destiation
and then again losing

00:47:37.520 --> 00:47:40.430
my brother, whom I love so much.

00:47:40.430 --> 00:47:42.580
I was in tears.

00:47:42.580 --> 00:47:45.020
And they didn't know what to do.

00:47:45.020 --> 00:47:48.127
So there, luckily, I found him.

00:47:51.109 --> 00:47:52.600
[CRYING]

00:47:52.600 --> 00:47:54.588
VINITA SUD BELANI: Sorry.

00:47:54.588 --> 00:47:58.080
You found him.

00:47:58.080 --> 00:47:59.500
RAVI CHOPRA: Yes.

00:47:59.500 --> 00:48:01.860
Sitting, crying.

00:48:01.860 --> 00:48:04.548
I hugged him.

00:48:04.548 --> 00:48:07.304
VINITA SUD BELANI: Sorry.

00:48:07.304 --> 00:48:08.970
So from Delhi station,
where did you go?

00:48:11.614 --> 00:48:13.030
RAVI CHOPRA: We
had nowhere to go,

00:48:13.030 --> 00:48:15.610
because my [INAUDIBLE]
didn't only remember that

00:48:15.610 --> 00:48:19.250
my [INAUDIBLE] name is
[INAUDIBLE] and she's there

00:48:19.250 --> 00:48:24.530
somewhere in [INAUDIBLE] and
that my [INAUDIBLE] has got

00:48:24.530 --> 00:48:28.710
a [? luggage ?] [? shop ?]
somewhere in [INAUDIBLE]..

00:48:28.710 --> 00:48:31.040
That's the only thing we knew.

00:48:31.040 --> 00:48:33.824
So we tagged along with
[INAUDIBLE] to the refugee

00:48:33.824 --> 00:48:34.615
camp in Karol Bagh.

00:48:34.615 --> 00:48:38.040
Those who have seen
Karol Bagh of today,

00:48:38.040 --> 00:48:40.730
there was nothing [INAUDIBLE]
or that shopping center.

00:48:40.730 --> 00:48:43.230
It was total bare land.

00:48:43.230 --> 00:48:45.020
That is where we had
that refugee camp.

00:48:45.020 --> 00:48:47.160
And that is where we stayed.

00:48:47.160 --> 00:48:51.510
And my [INAUDIBLE] would go
in the morning to [INAUDIBLE]

00:48:51.510 --> 00:48:56.620
and find out from every
[? luggage ?] [? shop, ?] do

00:48:56.620 --> 00:48:58.220
you know [INAUDIBLE]?

00:48:58.220 --> 00:49:00.100
Do you know [INAUDIBLE]?

00:49:00.100 --> 00:49:02.360
She's my [INAUDIBLE].

00:49:02.360 --> 00:49:03.774
VINITA SUD BELANI:
Amazing woman.

00:49:03.774 --> 00:49:05.130
RAVI CHOPRA: Yeah.

00:49:05.130 --> 00:49:11.280
So then one morning,
the gentleman

00:49:11.280 --> 00:49:14.920
said, yes, that's the name
of my wife, [INAUDIBLE]..

00:49:14.920 --> 00:49:18.140
And then he said is [? this ?]
younger sister's [INAUDIBLE]??

00:49:18.140 --> 00:49:20.270
My mother's name is [INAUDIBLE].

00:49:20.270 --> 00:49:21.264
He said yes.

00:49:21.264 --> 00:49:23.180
And then my [INAUDIBLE]
was literally in tears

00:49:23.180 --> 00:49:26.300
and introduced
herself and told her

00:49:26.300 --> 00:49:29.140
that I have brought
his children here.

00:49:29.140 --> 00:49:31.060
And that same evening,
my [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:31.060 --> 00:49:34.960
and my cousin's sister
came to the refugee camp

00:49:34.960 --> 00:49:39.400
and took us in a
[INAUDIBLE] to her home.

00:49:39.400 --> 00:49:45.390
And [INAUDIBLE]

00:49:45.390 --> 00:49:48.940
And we were in rags,
stinking clothes.

00:49:48.940 --> 00:49:53.990
So we changed, and we
got the new clothes.

00:49:53.990 --> 00:50:01.100
And then [INAUDIBLE] I ask you
a question, just what would

00:50:01.100 --> 00:50:04.420
be your feeling as
a mother when you

00:50:04.420 --> 00:50:10.560
know the children you are taken
as dead have arrived safely?

00:50:10.560 --> 00:50:13.710
All mothers, just put
yourself in that situation.

00:50:13.710 --> 00:50:17.120
How did my mother
take that news?

00:50:17.120 --> 00:50:22.750
That is two first-born who were
taken as dead have arrived.

00:50:22.750 --> 00:50:24.000
VINITA SUD BELANI: Incredible.

00:50:24.000 --> 00:50:26.410
RAVI CHOPRA: [INAUDIBLE] this is
kind of story for [INAUDIBLE]----

00:50:26.410 --> 00:50:28.380
VINITA SUD BELANI: I
can't begin to imagine

00:50:28.380 --> 00:50:29.740
how your mother must feel.

00:50:29.740 --> 00:50:33.480
RAVI CHOPRA: From what Guneeta
and [INAUDIBLE] told us,

00:50:33.480 --> 00:50:37.000
so many [INAUDIBLE]
were massacred.

00:50:37.000 --> 00:50:42.970
Millions were disturbed and
affected, badly affected,

00:50:42.970 --> 00:50:44.310
just kind of--

00:50:44.310 --> 00:50:49.450
and thanks to 1947
Archive that these things

00:50:49.450 --> 00:50:50.700
are being compiled.

00:50:50.700 --> 00:50:52.820
And I was one of
the first of one.

00:50:52.820 --> 00:50:55.616
Guneeta came and
recorded my story.

00:50:55.616 --> 00:50:56.740
VINITA SUD BELANI: That's--

00:50:56.740 --> 00:50:59.047
well, you're a first
in many ways, Ravi ji.

00:50:59.047 --> 00:51:00.880
But in your whole story,
you haven't told us

00:51:00.880 --> 00:51:01.700
about your father.

00:51:01.700 --> 00:51:03.549
What happened to him?

00:51:03.549 --> 00:51:05.090
RAVI CHOPRA: My
father, as mentioned,

00:51:05.090 --> 00:51:06.340
had gone to [INAUDIBLE].

00:51:06.340 --> 00:51:10.750
So from there, he checked
up the [INAUDIBLE]

00:51:10.750 --> 00:51:12.500
so that we have
left [INAUDIBLE]..

00:51:12.500 --> 00:51:16.470
But he didn't know what
happened after that.

00:51:16.470 --> 00:51:21.460
His influence with the
police and the help of army,

00:51:21.460 --> 00:51:25.230
he flew to Delhi.

00:51:25.230 --> 00:51:32.220
But [INAUDIBLE] we are putting
that in our "Parting" play.

00:51:32.220 --> 00:51:36.000
Everybody used to be
glued to the radio station

00:51:36.000 --> 00:51:38.315
to know about
their kith and kin,

00:51:38.315 --> 00:51:39.440
say whether they are alive.

00:51:39.440 --> 00:51:40.064
Where are they?

00:51:40.064 --> 00:51:44.250
Because even from the camp's
announcement used to be there.

00:51:44.250 --> 00:51:47.510
Radio stations all
the time, 24 hours,

00:51:47.510 --> 00:51:49.729
who are looking for this son?

00:51:49.729 --> 00:51:51.520
Was somebody looking
for a mother, somebody

00:51:51.520 --> 00:51:52.500
looking for the father?

00:51:52.500 --> 00:51:58.240
For 24 hours, a radio station
broadcast would be there.

00:51:58.240 --> 00:52:03.630
That is how my father learned
that we have reached India,

00:52:03.630 --> 00:52:05.580
but we didn't know where he is.

00:52:05.580 --> 00:52:10.650
So it is only when he
came to Delhi that we

00:52:10.650 --> 00:52:13.050
got to united as a family.

00:52:13.050 --> 00:52:14.300
VINITA SUD BELANI: Incredible.

00:52:14.300 --> 00:52:17.920
RAVI CHOPRA: And we all met
in a place, [INAUDIBLE],,

00:52:17.920 --> 00:52:20.699
where my grandfather was the
manager of a sugar mills.

00:52:20.699 --> 00:52:21.990
VINITA SUD BELANI: Sugar mills.

00:52:21.990 --> 00:52:24.610
RAVI CHOPRA: [INAUDIBLE]
sugar mills, yes.

00:52:24.610 --> 00:52:26.860
VINITA SUD BELANI: So my
father also moved from Lahore

00:52:26.860 --> 00:52:27.430
to Amritsar.

00:52:27.430 --> 00:52:30.830
And my grandfather was also the
manager of the sugar mill in

00:52:30.830 --> 00:52:31.616
[INAUDIBLE].

00:52:34.300 --> 00:52:36.360
We were destined to
meet no matter what.

00:52:36.360 --> 00:52:38.090
We're all part of family.

00:52:38.090 --> 00:52:42.051
So thank you so much
for sharing that story.

00:52:42.051 --> 00:52:42.550
I just--

00:52:42.550 --> 00:52:44.920
[APPLAUSE]

00:52:46.820 --> 00:52:52.040
[INAUDIBLE] The reason
we bring up this story

00:52:52.040 --> 00:52:56.300
is because Ravi ji,
as he mentioned,

00:52:56.300 --> 00:52:58.880
was one of the first people
interviewed by the archive.

00:52:58.880 --> 00:53:03.410
His story is one of the earliest
recorded in the archive.

00:53:03.410 --> 00:53:06.290
He had an entire
career in the army

00:53:06.290 --> 00:53:08.360
and retired as a Major General.

00:53:08.360 --> 00:53:11.690
And then he started a second
career here in the Bay Area.

00:53:11.690 --> 00:53:14.390
Tell us about that one.

00:53:14.390 --> 00:53:16.994
RAVI CHOPRA: You see, when
I came to the United States,

00:53:16.994 --> 00:53:18.410
nobody would take
me as a general.

00:53:18.410 --> 00:53:20.660
[LAUGHTER]

00:53:20.660 --> 00:53:23.120
So I chose my next best passion.

00:53:23.120 --> 00:53:28.010
Even when I was in service,
I used to write plays--

00:53:28.010 --> 00:53:30.170
small skits, not plays--

00:53:30.170 --> 00:53:32.030
skits, act in plays.

00:53:32.030 --> 00:53:37.040
And when I grew up in
rank, then my priorities

00:53:37.040 --> 00:53:40.370
changed, because I had other
things to take care of.

00:53:40.370 --> 00:53:41.760
But the passion remained.

00:53:41.760 --> 00:53:45.590
So when I came here, this
was my second best career,

00:53:45.590 --> 00:53:46.845
which I thought I would join.

00:53:46.845 --> 00:53:48.290
I joined dancing groups.

00:53:48.290 --> 00:53:51.990
I joined a theater group
with [INAUDIBLE],, with you.

00:53:51.990 --> 00:53:53.320
And one of [INAUDIBLE].

00:53:53.320 --> 00:53:54.695
VINITA SUD BELANI:
So I just want

00:53:54.695 --> 00:53:56.960
to tell everybody that in
the play that we are doing

00:53:56.960 --> 00:53:59.600
about the partition,
which is made up

00:53:59.600 --> 00:54:03.830
of true-life accounts
of people like Ravi ji,

00:54:03.830 --> 00:54:08.720
he is actually playing the role
of a very kind and benevolent

00:54:08.720 --> 00:54:10.150
Muslim Pakistani.

00:54:14.510 --> 00:54:17.660
RAVI CHOPRA: In that role,
I'm reliving my partition life

00:54:17.660 --> 00:54:20.240
in this role, because
here, also, I'm performing

00:54:20.240 --> 00:54:22.230
the role of a Muslim gentlemen.

00:54:22.230 --> 00:54:25.200
There, the Muslim saved
my life as Hindus.

00:54:25.200 --> 00:54:28.174
Here as a Muslim, I'm
saving Hindus' life.

00:54:28.174 --> 00:54:28.840
I'm one of them.

00:54:28.840 --> 00:54:29.712
[APPLAUSE]

00:54:29.712 --> 00:54:30.920
VINITA SUD BELANI: Thank you.

00:54:30.920 --> 00:54:32.037
Thank you so much, Ravi ji.

00:54:32.037 --> 00:54:33.500
RAVI CHOPRA: Thank
you, [INAUDIBLE]..

00:54:33.500 --> 00:54:36.110
VINITA SUD BELANI: So it was an
honor to have Ravi ji on stage

00:54:36.110 --> 00:54:37.850
with us and sharing his story.

00:54:37.850 --> 00:54:39.410
I just wanted to
bring him onstage

00:54:39.410 --> 00:54:43.130
because I wanted to
show what the power is

00:54:43.130 --> 00:54:47.750
of a story told in real time
between people and making

00:54:47.750 --> 00:54:49.176
that connect.

00:54:49.176 --> 00:54:51.050
And these are the stories
that we are telling

00:54:51.050 --> 00:54:53.570
in the play about the parting.

00:54:53.570 --> 00:54:56.630
There is music and
dance and a lot

00:54:56.630 --> 00:55:00.170
of audio-visual, very
high-tech elements in there.

00:55:00.170 --> 00:55:02.030
But fundamentally,
these are the stories

00:55:02.030 --> 00:55:04.940
that make up the real
history of the partition.

00:55:04.940 --> 00:55:07.010
And so I want to
now introduce you

00:55:07.010 --> 00:55:11.060
to the person who is the writer
and the director of the play

00:55:11.060 --> 00:55:13.160
and let him talk about
the play himself.

00:55:13.160 --> 00:55:15.990
My great honor to welcome
on stage, Salil Singh.

00:55:15.990 --> 00:55:18.702
[APPLAUSE]

00:55:20.510 --> 00:55:23.180
I am not going to
introduce Salil.

00:55:23.180 --> 00:55:25.730
His words are going to be
so mesmerizing that you're

00:55:25.730 --> 00:55:28.760
going to look him up on Google
as soon as you get out of here.

00:55:28.760 --> 00:55:30.170
So take it away, Salil.

00:55:30.170 --> 00:55:32.270
SALIL SINGH: Thank you, Vinita.

00:55:32.270 --> 00:55:34.970
Several years ago,
as I became familiar

00:55:34.970 --> 00:55:37.160
with the work of
the archive, I began

00:55:37.160 --> 00:55:41.390
to work on a script for a play
that would dramatize stories

00:55:41.390 --> 00:55:45.800
embedded in the experience of
partition, stories of lives

00:55:45.800 --> 00:55:51.230
deeply, irreversibly redirected,
torn as a consequence of lines

00:55:51.230 --> 00:55:53.070
drawn on a map.

00:55:53.070 --> 00:55:55.470
I realized quickly
several important things.

00:55:55.470 --> 00:55:59.210
First, it's an immense
subject matter played out

00:55:59.210 --> 00:56:03.050
on a vast canvas
of a subcontinent,

00:56:03.050 --> 00:56:07.340
and that a terrible silence
has engulfed these stories

00:56:07.340 --> 00:56:09.260
across the decades--

00:56:09.260 --> 00:56:13.010
a silence that has perpetuated
through a combination

00:56:13.010 --> 00:56:17.540
of regret, guilt,
shame, loss, trauma,

00:56:17.540 --> 00:56:22.000
incomprehensible suffering,
destruction, and death.

00:56:22.000 --> 00:56:25.570
And finally, there is
a brief window of time

00:56:25.570 --> 00:56:29.980
in which it is still possible
to gather people on a stage

00:56:29.980 --> 00:56:36.770
and in an audience as they have
a living memory of this event.

00:56:36.770 --> 00:56:41.300
And it's our chance to speak
across generations and nations,

00:56:41.300 --> 00:56:43.940
religions and divisions.

00:56:43.940 --> 00:56:45.770
So this was my mandate.

00:56:45.770 --> 00:56:47.900
I began to write
a play that would

00:56:47.900 --> 00:56:51.490
unlock some of these stories.

00:56:51.490 --> 00:56:53.580
The play is called
"The Parting."

00:56:53.580 --> 00:56:56.850
And I'll really talk to
you about how it begins.

00:56:56.850 --> 00:56:59.610
It begins in a
deserted wasteland

00:56:59.610 --> 00:57:03.780
in which characters
are sleeping all

00:57:03.780 --> 00:57:06.300
across the expanse of the stage.

00:57:06.300 --> 00:57:12.160
Through it walk a young
girl and her grandmother.

00:57:12.160 --> 00:57:15.370
The young girl dares
to ask a question which

00:57:15.370 --> 00:57:19.180
will awaken the ghosts
of these stories buried

00:57:19.180 --> 00:57:21.130
in the fog of history.

00:57:21.130 --> 00:57:26.940
And her question is, I want to
know what happened that year.

00:57:26.940 --> 00:57:32.430
All across this landscape,
whispers begin to surface.

00:57:32.430 --> 00:57:34.890
At first, they're warnings.

00:57:34.890 --> 00:57:36.990
They don't wish to be awakened.

00:57:36.990 --> 00:57:41.600
These are ghosts who are
very happy living undercover.

00:57:41.600 --> 00:57:45.940
1947, 1947.

00:57:45.940 --> 00:57:47.320
Why remember?

00:57:47.320 --> 00:57:50.140
Let sleeping dogs
lie, or you will hear

00:57:50.140 --> 00:57:51.550
them howling through the night.

00:57:51.550 --> 00:57:52.870
Who cares to know?

00:57:52.870 --> 00:57:54.400
Who dares to name it?

00:57:54.400 --> 00:57:56.740
Too much time has gone by.

00:57:56.740 --> 00:57:58.420
No one can even remember.

00:57:58.420 --> 00:58:00.550
We have tried so hard to forget.

00:58:00.550 --> 00:58:04.320
Some things are
better left forgotten.

00:58:04.320 --> 00:58:06.520
1947.

00:58:06.520 --> 00:58:09.280
If you do, it'll be too
much, too little, too late.

00:58:09.280 --> 00:58:10.090
It's too far.

00:58:10.090 --> 00:58:11.260
It's too long.

00:58:11.260 --> 00:58:12.280
Too many have suffered.

00:58:12.280 --> 00:58:13.520
Too many have died.

00:58:13.520 --> 00:58:15.870
Too many that lived who
would rather have died.

00:58:15.870 --> 00:58:18.280
1947.

00:58:18.280 --> 00:58:20.950
If you try to
remember, you will rake

00:58:20.950 --> 00:58:24.510
the coals and fan the flames.

00:58:24.510 --> 00:58:29.140
But the girl asks, "if
you don't remember,

00:58:29.140 --> 00:58:32.330
how will I know who I am?"

00:58:32.330 --> 00:58:35.380
And all the whispers
stop at that moment.

00:58:35.380 --> 00:58:38.350
This is the key that unlocks
the rest of the play.

00:58:38.350 --> 00:58:41.770
So this is what I had for a
shape, a structure, to a play.

00:58:41.770 --> 00:58:47.770
It was waiting to meet a
visionary producer, Vinita,

00:58:47.770 --> 00:58:49.810
a theater company,
EnActe, which was

00:58:49.810 --> 00:58:54.250
ready to take a very huge risk
and put this out there, a dance

00:58:54.250 --> 00:58:59.410
theater company, Noorani Dance,
under Farah Yasmeen Shaikh, who

00:58:59.410 --> 00:59:03.400
were inspired enough to join
forces and, in some ways,

00:59:03.400 --> 00:59:07.270
give me this amazing,
in some ways,

00:59:07.270 --> 00:59:10.990
humbling and
ennobling experience

00:59:10.990 --> 00:59:12.820
of spearheading this project.

00:59:12.820 --> 00:59:15.430
The production is
in full swing, and I

00:59:15.430 --> 00:59:17.290
invite you all to
come see it when

00:59:17.290 --> 00:59:20.200
it does open in the Bay Area.

00:59:20.200 --> 00:59:21.910
What I'd like to
do at this point,

00:59:21.910 --> 00:59:26.650
though, is to bring
back on stage Anurag.

00:59:26.650 --> 00:59:29.770
You have known him as your
gracious host for this morning.

00:59:29.770 --> 00:59:33.610
He's also my story
development collaborator,

00:59:33.610 --> 00:59:38.680
who has helped me understand
what stories to tell,

00:59:38.680 --> 00:59:42.070
what kinds of
narratives to weave back

00:59:42.070 --> 00:59:47.950
into this play that would dare
to paint an image of a moment

00:59:47.950 --> 00:59:52.780
in time, which is grand
enough, satisfying enough,

00:59:52.780 --> 00:59:55.900
honest enough, brutal
enough to do justice

00:59:55.900 --> 00:59:57.230
to this moment in history.

00:59:57.230 --> 00:59:59.530
Anurag, will you
speak a word about how

00:59:59.530 --> 01:00:02.110
you came to select the
kinds of stories that

01:00:02.110 --> 01:00:03.437
have become a part of the play?

01:00:03.437 --> 01:00:04.270
ANURAG WADEHRA: Yes.

01:00:04.270 --> 01:00:05.460
Thank you.

01:00:05.460 --> 01:00:08.230
I have been passionate
about the subject.

01:00:08.230 --> 01:00:11.230
In the last 20 years, I
have been collecting stories

01:00:11.230 --> 01:00:15.580
and curating stories and also
writing some short stories

01:00:15.580 --> 01:00:19.210
on the matter, since it's a
subject was close to my heart.

01:00:19.210 --> 01:00:22.390
And when I was invited to
participate in this project,

01:00:22.390 --> 01:00:27.070
I realized that through the
support of Vinita and EnActe

01:00:27.070 --> 01:00:30.250
as well as direction,
what was possible

01:00:30.250 --> 01:00:32.260
was to cherry pick some
of the stories that

01:00:32.260 --> 01:00:35.710
could shape the telling of
such a massive incident.

01:00:35.710 --> 01:00:38.710
And we deliberately
chose stories

01:00:38.710 --> 01:00:40.730
from a variety of sources.

01:00:40.730 --> 01:00:43.150
Some of these are obviously
imaginative stories

01:00:43.150 --> 01:00:46.060
created by me and others
over the years based

01:00:46.060 --> 01:00:48.190
on lived experience
of millions of people.

01:00:48.190 --> 01:00:49.990
Some of these are
actually ripped

01:00:49.990 --> 01:00:52.600
from the headlines of that era.

01:00:52.600 --> 01:00:55.510
For example, a story which is
the centerpiece of the play

01:00:55.510 --> 01:01:00.970
is star-crossed lovers of
Zainab and Butta Singh.

01:01:00.970 --> 01:01:03.790
Butta Singh was a Sikh
farmer who gave shelter

01:01:03.790 --> 01:01:07.180
to a Muslim woman, and who,
after many years of living

01:01:07.180 --> 01:01:10.390
together, she was forcibly
sent back to Pakistan,

01:01:10.390 --> 01:01:13.600
and how he crossed the
boundaries of religion

01:01:13.600 --> 01:01:16.470
and state to get to
reunite with her.

01:01:16.470 --> 01:01:18.310
That's a true story.

01:01:18.310 --> 01:01:19.900
It was popular at it's time--

01:01:19.900 --> 01:01:20.940
very contested.

01:01:20.940 --> 01:01:22.990
Another that example
is a story that

01:01:22.990 --> 01:01:25.405
was curated from
historical archives--

01:01:25.405 --> 01:01:30.490
a story of a British army
limb fitter, [INAUDIBLE],,

01:01:30.490 --> 01:01:34.060
who was actually shuttling
between India and Pakistan

01:01:34.060 --> 01:01:36.170
armies for almost
a decade or more

01:01:36.170 --> 01:01:38.620
and not being able to
reconcile whether he

01:01:38.620 --> 01:01:40.750
was a Pakistani or an
Indian [INAUDIBLE]..

01:01:40.750 --> 01:01:42.250
And that was the
true story straight

01:01:42.250 --> 01:01:47.460
from research that was done by
many scholars as an example.

01:01:47.460 --> 01:01:51.610
Yet another story around
how a brother is trying

01:01:51.610 --> 01:01:55.640
to protect the honor of
his sister and the price he

01:01:55.640 --> 01:01:58.180
has to pay for doing that,
and the kind of question

01:01:58.180 --> 01:01:59.260
he faces that.

01:01:59.260 --> 01:02:03.800
That's an imagined story from
experiences of many people.

01:02:03.800 --> 01:02:07.450
And finally, stories of
Hindu and Muslim neighbors

01:02:07.450 --> 01:02:11.530
that we kind of reconstructed
from historical narratives that

01:02:11.530 --> 01:02:15.190
talk about how could neighbors
who were living together,

01:02:15.190 --> 01:02:18.380
Hindus and Muslims, lose
trust in each other suddenly?

01:02:18.380 --> 01:02:21.070
And what would it take
to bring the trust back?

01:02:21.070 --> 01:02:21.945
Was it even possible?

01:02:21.945 --> 01:02:23.320
So these were some
of the stories

01:02:23.320 --> 01:02:24.820
that we kind of
compiled together.

01:02:24.820 --> 01:02:27.430
None of these were
selected with the intention

01:02:27.430 --> 01:02:29.950
of horror or shock,
although many of them

01:02:29.950 --> 01:02:31.360
are horrifying and shocking.

01:02:31.360 --> 01:02:33.190
We selected them
from a wide variety

01:02:33.190 --> 01:02:36.340
to represent the range
of possible experiences.

01:02:36.340 --> 01:02:39.730
Ultimately, the idea was to
ask the question that Salil

01:02:39.730 --> 01:02:41.680
had put in the beginning.

01:02:41.680 --> 01:02:43.310
Why did this happen?

01:02:43.310 --> 01:02:44.830
And how do we make sense of it?

01:02:44.830 --> 01:02:47.455
So that was the intention
of these stories.

01:02:47.455 --> 01:02:48.130
Thank you.

01:02:48.130 --> 01:02:48.740
SALIL SINGH: Pleasure.

01:02:48.740 --> 01:02:49.239
Thank you.

01:02:49.239 --> 01:02:51.000
[APPLAUSE]

01:02:51.000 --> 01:02:55.300
So you can expect a poetic
rendering of these stories

01:02:55.300 --> 01:02:57.130
when you come to
see "The Parting"--

01:02:57.130 --> 01:03:03.940
something that combines poetry,
dance, theater, acting, words,

01:03:03.940 --> 01:03:06.371
and beautiful music.

01:03:06.371 --> 01:03:07.870
I would like to
invite at this point

01:03:07.870 --> 01:03:11.050
two young ladies who've been
waiting very patiently, Mira

01:03:11.050 --> 01:03:12.130
and Athena.

01:03:12.130 --> 01:03:15.220
They are part of Noorani Dance.

01:03:15.220 --> 01:03:15.880
Let me clarify.

01:03:15.880 --> 01:03:17.380
What they're about
to share with you

01:03:17.380 --> 01:03:19.370
is a little performance piece.

01:03:19.370 --> 01:03:21.910
It's not from the
production of "The Parting."

01:03:21.910 --> 01:03:26.370
It is their way of connecting
to the stories and the material

01:03:26.370 --> 01:03:28.870
and the events around 1947.

01:03:28.870 --> 01:03:32.894
And they've been working on it
as a dance interpretive piece.

01:03:32.894 --> 01:03:34.376
[APPLAUSE]

01:03:36.352 --> 01:03:39.316
[MUSIC PLAYING]

01:03:44.260 --> 01:03:47.990
NARRATOR: The train to
Lahore was very difficult.

01:03:47.990 --> 01:03:51.120
The train stopped at
multiple locations.

01:03:51.120 --> 01:03:54.980
And at one point, we'd
looked out the broken windows

01:03:54.980 --> 01:03:57.530
to see the train
surrounded by people

01:03:57.530 --> 01:04:02.070
with weapons in their hands,
ready to slaughter us,

01:04:02.070 --> 01:04:03.940
the passengers.

01:04:03.940 --> 01:04:07.300
The train driver managed
to negotiate with the mob

01:04:07.300 --> 01:04:11.410
and found a way for the
train and the passengers

01:04:11.410 --> 01:04:15.460
to reach its destination safely.

01:04:15.460 --> 01:04:19.960
When we arrived, we
saw bloody train cars

01:04:19.960 --> 01:04:22.510
and learned that some
of our dearest friends

01:04:22.510 --> 01:04:24.820
had been killed on the way.

01:04:31.060 --> 01:04:33.750
We arrived at the
crowded station,

01:04:33.750 --> 01:04:38.200
carrying whatever we managed to
hold in our arms from our home.

01:04:38.200 --> 01:04:40.450
I held to my six-year-old
daughter's hand

01:04:40.450 --> 01:04:44.170
with such a tight grasp,
she was complaining.

01:04:44.170 --> 01:04:46.090
We pushed through the crowds.

01:04:46.090 --> 01:04:48.400
Just as I stepped
onto the train,

01:04:48.400 --> 01:04:52.180
I felt my arm being pulled
back by the force of the crowd.

01:04:52.180 --> 01:04:54.850
I tried to hold on
with all my strength.

01:04:54.850 --> 01:04:59.920
But the grip was loosening,
our sweaty palms not helping,

01:04:59.920 --> 01:05:02.280
nor the herd of
people around me.

01:05:05.570 --> 01:05:09.300
The train was
starting to move, even

01:05:09.300 --> 01:05:12.100
though not all
were on the train,

01:05:12.100 --> 01:05:17.420
and even though my daughter
was not on the train.

01:05:17.420 --> 01:05:19.732
I never saw her again.

01:05:29.840 --> 01:05:33.500
I was 11 years old when
partition was announced.

01:05:33.500 --> 01:05:36.420
While we were playing
near the railway station,

01:05:36.420 --> 01:05:39.935
we were told that a nearby train
was being attacked by a mob.

01:05:39.935 --> 01:05:43.970
We rushed to the tragic
scene, and saw men, women,

01:05:43.970 --> 01:05:45.990
and children being
looted and murdered.

01:05:45.990 --> 01:05:48.560
Or All we could
hear were screams.

01:05:48.560 --> 01:05:52.380
And all we saw were
piles of dead bodies.

01:05:52.380 --> 01:05:54.820
I remember seeing a
baby who was still

01:05:54.820 --> 01:05:58.058
latched to its dead mother.

01:06:08.904 --> 01:06:12.848
Finally, it was our
turn to board the train.

01:06:12.848 --> 01:06:16.299
We were stuffed in like
cotton bales in a gunny sack.

01:06:16.299 --> 01:06:18.271
The doors of the
train were barricaded

01:06:18.271 --> 01:06:19.750
so no one could get out.

01:06:19.750 --> 01:06:22.708
The three-day journey was
filled with tribulations.

01:06:22.708 --> 01:06:25.173
The train was nearly
massacred just

01:06:25.173 --> 01:06:27.145
before the end of the journey.

01:06:27.145 --> 01:06:29.610
When we had almost
reached our destination,

01:06:29.610 --> 01:06:32.568
a group of insurgents
broke into the train

01:06:32.568 --> 01:06:34.120
through one of the
barricaded doors.

01:06:34.120 --> 01:06:37.215
Their swords were
covered in a soft cloth.

01:06:37.215 --> 01:06:41.990
And they said if the train
going to India comes unharmed,

01:06:41.990 --> 01:06:44.330
we will not harm anyone.

01:06:44.330 --> 01:06:46.838
Luckily, that train
was not harmed.

01:06:55.202 --> 01:07:01.340
When we reached our destination
and we got off the train,

01:07:01.340 --> 01:07:05.120
instead of running
for food and water,

01:07:05.120 --> 01:07:09.830
people knelt on the ground and
offered prayers of gratitude

01:07:09.830 --> 01:07:14.684
that we had made it safely.

01:07:14.684 --> 01:07:17.174
[NON-ENGLISH SINGING]

01:07:54.524 --> 01:07:57.512
[APPLAUSE]

